{"title_page": "Michael Proctor (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Michael Proctor}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Michael Proctor\n| image = Michael Proctor.jpg\n| image_size = 240\n| caption = Proctor playing for [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in [[Jody Craddock]]'s testimonial match in 2014\n| fullname = Michael Anthony Proctor<ref name=\"Hugman2008-09\">{{Cite book\n | editor-first = Barry J.\n | editor-last = Hugman\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2008\u201309\n | year = 2008\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | isbn = 978-1-84596-324-8\n | page = 340 }}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|10|3|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman2008-09\"/>\n| birth_place = [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=11}}<ref name=\"Hugman2008-09\"/>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20131997\n| youthclubs1 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| years1 = 1997\u20132004\n| years2 = 2000\u20132001\n| years3 = 2001\n| years4 = 2001\u20132002\n| years5 = 2002\n| years6 = 2004\u20132005\n| years7 = 2005\n| years8 = 2005\u20132007\n| years9 = 2007\n| years10 = 2007\u20132009\n| clubs1 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]] (loan)\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] (loan)\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[York City F.C.|York City]] (loan)\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)\n| clubs6 = [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan)\n| clubs8 = [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]]\n| clubs9 = \u2192 [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] (loan)\n| clubs10 = [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]]\n| caps1 = 38\n| caps2 = 5\n| caps3 = 12\n| caps4 = 41\n| caps5 = 12\n| caps6 = 45\n| caps7 = 4\n| caps8 = 28\n| caps9 = 9\n| caps10 = 58\n| goals1 = 3\n| goals2 = 1\n| goals3 = 4\n| goals4 = 14\n| goals5 = 4\n| goals6 = 7\n| goals7 = 2\n| goals8 = 5\n| goals9 = 2\n| goals10 = 12\n| totalcaps = 264\n| totalgoals = 54\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 =\n| nationalcaps1 =\n| nationalgoals1 =\n| club-update = 20:49, 27 April 2009 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Michael Anthony Proctor''' (born 3 October 1980) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Sunderland===\nBorn in [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]], [[Tyne and Wear]], Proctor started his career with his hometown club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in their [[youth system]] and signed a professional contract with them on 29 October 1997.<ref name=\"Hugman2008-09\"/> He made his [[first team]] debut for Sunderland against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] on 11 November 1998, which finished as a 1\u20131 draw.<ref name=\"Michael Proctor 1998-99\">{{cite web\n| title = Michael Proctor\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=128&playerid=14789\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref> He was loaned to [[Denmark|Danish]] side [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]] in 2000 to recuperate from a cruciate ligament injury.<ref name=\"Michael Proctor\">{{cite web\n| title = Michael Proctor\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=14789\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Proctor set to apply lower league lessons in higher academy\n |url        = http://sport.independent.co.uk/football/coca_cola/article124130.ece\n |publisher  = The Independent on Sunday\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n |date       = 11 January 2003\n |first      = Tim\n |last       = Rice\n |location   = London\n}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He joined [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] on loan in March 2001, making his debut against [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]], in which he scored in a 4\u20132 win.<ref name=\"Michael Proctor 2000-01\">{{cite web\n| title = Michael Proctor\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=130&playerid=14789\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref> He finished this loan spell with four goals in 12 appearances.<ref name=\"Michael Proctor\"/> He played at [[York City F.C.|York City]] on loan during the [[2001-02 in English football|2001\u201302]] season, making his debut in a 1\u20130 defeat against [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]].<ref name=\"Michael Proctor 2001-02\">{{cite web\n| title = Michael Proctor\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=131&playerid=14789\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref> He finished this spell with 49 appearances and 14 goals, making him York's top scorer for the season.<ref name=\"York 2001/2002 player appearances\">{{cite web\n| title = York 2001/2002 player appearances\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/squad_season.sd?seasonid=131&teamid=2910\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref> He joined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on loan in August 2002.<ref name=\"Law brings in Sunderland striker on loan\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Law brings in Sunderland striker on loan\n| url = http://www.bradfordcityfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10266~260858,00.html\n| publisher = Bradford City AFC\n| date = 17 November 2004\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He scored the winning goal on his debut as Bradford defeated [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] 2\u20131,<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Striker set for longer stay\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/8/28/122548.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130505155640/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/8/28/122548.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 28 August 2002\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref> and became a favourite among fans,<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Mauled by Black Cats\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2003/12/27/104558.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130505082355/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2003/12/27/104558.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 27 December 2003\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref> players,<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = We need to keep Proctor \u2013 Danny\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/10/15/120645.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130505063457/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/10/15/120645.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 15 October 2002\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref> and the board.<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Gibb rules out being City's loan arranger\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2003/10/25/106399.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130505154544/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2003/10/25/106399.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 25 October 2002\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref> He scored a total of four goals in 12 games during his two-month spell, including a late equaliser as nine-man City drew 2\u20132 with [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]],<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Proctor pulls off great escape\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/9/21/121515.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130421105459/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/9/21/121515.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 21 April 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 21 September 2002\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref> but he returned to Sunderland when manager [[Howard Wilkinson]] blocked another month's extension to the loan.<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Law to replace Proctor\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/10/26/120153.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130505083928/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/10/26/120153.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 26 October 2002\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nHe scored the winner for Sunderland in their 2\u20131 win over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 15 December 2002.<ref name=\"Liverpool impersonate a crisis\">{{cite news\n| title = Liverpool impersonate a crisis\n| url = http://football.guardian.co.uk/Match_Report/0,,-40826,00.html\n| publisher = Guardian Unlimited\n| date = 16 December 2002\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008\n| location=London\n| first=David\n| last=Hopps}}</ref> One unfortunate claim to fame occurred whilst playing for Sunderland in 2003, in a 3\u20131 defeat to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], where Proctor scored two own goals within just five minutes.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Proctor gifts Addicks win\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2395397/Charlton-enjoy-own-goal-feast.html\n|publisher=BBC Sport\n|accessdate=20 January 2008\n|date=1 February 2003}}</ref>\n\n===Rotherham United and Hartlepool United===\nProctor left Sunderland in February 2004, joining [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] in a swap deal for [[Darren Byfield]].<ref name=\"- One In & One Out\">\n{{cite news\n| title = \u2013 One In & One Out\n| url = http://www.themillers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10360~484135,00.html\n| publisher = Rotherham United FC\n| date = 6 February 2004\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He joined [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on a month's loan deal in February 2005.<ref name=\"Swindon sign Proctor on loan deal\">{{cite news\n| title = Swindon sign Proctor on loan deal\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/swindon_town/4287923.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 22 February 2005\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> Swindon could not afford to extend his loan at the club and he returned to Rotherham in March.<ref name=\"Proctor returns after loan spell\">{{cite news\n| title = Proctor returns after loan spell\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rotherham_utd/4369031.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 21 March 2005\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> He later moved to [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] on a free transfer in July 2005.<ref name=\"Hartlepool sign striker Proctor\">{{cite news\n| title = Hartlepool sign striker Proctor\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hartlepool_united/4673225.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 11 July 2005\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> He was best remembered by Hartlepool fans for scoring twice in a 3\u20131 over local rivals [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] in a [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] tie early in his Pools' career.<ref name=\"hartlepool\">{{cite news\n|title=Pools stalk Stag\n|url=http://www.hartlepoolmail.co.uk/sport/Pools-stalk-Stag.2895092.jp\n|publisher=Hartlepool Mail\n|date=22 May 2007\n|accessdate=20 January 2008\n|first=Richard\n|last=Watts}}</ref> He played just 32 games in two seasons for Hartlepool, scoring ten goals, before he was one of ten players released by [[Danny Wilson (footballer, born 1960)|Danny Wilson]].<ref name=\"hartlepool\"/>\n\n===Wrexham===\nProctor joined [[Football League Two|League Two]] club [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] on a month's loan in March 2007.<ref name=\"Wrexham swoop for striker Proctor\">{{cite news\n| title = Wrexham swoop for striker Proctor\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wrexham/6457765.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 23 March 2007\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> This loan was extended until the end of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307]] season in April.<ref name=\"Proctor to stay on with Wrexham\">{{cite news\n| title = Proctor to stay on with Wrexham\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wrexham/6596603.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 26 April 2007\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> During this spell he scored two vital goals for Wrexham in their eventually successful survival bid. These were the winning goal in the 1\u20130 victory at local rivals [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] and the third goal in the Welsh club's 3\u20131 victory over [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] which preserved the club's [[The Football League|Football League]] status. He was released by Hartlepool in May 2007 and expressed an interest in joining Wrexham permanently.<ref name=\"Pools boss Wilson swings his axe\">{{cite news\n| title = Pools boss Wilson swings his axe\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hartlepool_united/6640219.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 9 May 2007\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |title       = Proctor signs three-year deal\n |url         = http://www.dailypost.co.uk/src/webroot/dailypost/sport-news/wrexham-fc/2007/05/22/proctor-signs-three-year-deal-50142-19151008/\n |publisher   = Daily Post\n |date        = 22 May 2007\n |accessdate  = 20 January 2008\n |first       = Mark\n |last        = Currie\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110720012235/http://www.dailypost.co.uk/src/webroot/dailypost/sport-news/wrexham-fc/2007/05/22/proctor-signs-three-year-deal-50142-19151008/\n |archivedate = 20 July 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> This move was confirmed in May 2007.<ref name=\"Wrexham complete Proctor capture\">{{cite news\n| title = Wrexham complete Proctor capture\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wrexham/6677211.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 21 May 2007\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> He was transfer listed by Wrexham in May 2008 following the club's relegation to the [[Football Conference]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wrexham/7367679.stm|title=Roberts and Llewellyn leave Reds |date=6 May 2008|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 May 2008}}</ref> despite finishing the season as the club's top scorer with 12 goals.<ref name=\"Wrexham 2007/2008 player appearances\">{{cite web\n| title = Wrexham 2007/2008 player appearances\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/squad_season.sd?seasonid=137&teamid=2859\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 7 July 2008}}</ref> In the summer of 2009 after talks with manager Dean Saunders, Proctor left the club by mutual consent.\n\n===Media Work===\n\nFrom the start of the 2014/15 season, Michael began to work as a co-host for [[Sun FM]]'s Into The Light football show, discussing all things [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] with the immensely talented duo of Stephen Goldsmith and Gareth Barker of Wise Men Say podcast fame. They arguably carried the show with Michael adding expert opinion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sun-fm.com/of-into-the-light-with-michael-proctor-.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607022640/http://www.sun-fm.com/of-into-the-light-with-michael-proctor-.php |archive-date=7 June 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This isn't an area of work Michael had intentionally planned on getting into after retiring, as he had previously been involved in coaching at East Durham College.<ref>http://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2015/june/where-are-they-now-michael-proctor</ref><ref>http://www.eastdurham.ac.uk/college_student_advances_to_next_round_of_bcs_trials</ref> Since becoming a frequent visitor to the Stadium of Light to undergo his media duties, Michael has begun to work closer with the [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] media team, most notably interviewing [[Jermain Defoe]] about his winning goal in a game against fierce rivals [[Newcastle United]].<ref>http://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2015/april/youtube-jermain-defoe-on-derby-goal</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Michael Proctor}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Proctor, Michael}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sunderland, Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hvidovre IF players]]\n[[Category:Halifax Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:York City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rotherham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hartlepool United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Wrexham A.F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Other uses|Michael Proctor}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Michael Proctor\n| image = Michael Proctor.jpg\n| image_size = 240\n| caption = Proctor playing for [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in [[Jody Craddock]]'s testimonial match in 2014\n| fullname = Michael Anthony Proctor<ref name=\"Hugman2008-09\">{{Cite book\n | editor-first = Barry J.\n | editor-last = Hugman\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2008\u201309\n | year = 2008\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | isbn = 978-1-84596-324-8\n | page = 340 }}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|10|3|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman2008-09\"/>\n| birth_place = [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=11}}<ref name=\"Hugman2008-09\"/>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20131997\n| youthclubs1 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| years1 = 1997\u20132004\n| years2 = 2000\u20132001\n| years3 = 2001\n| years4 = 2001\u20132002\n| years5 = 2002\n| years6 = 2004\u20132005\n| years7 = 2005\n| years8 = 2005\u20132007\n| years9 = 2007\n| years10 = 2007\u20132009\n| clubs1 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]] (loan)\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] (loan)\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[York City F.C.|York City]] (loan)\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)\n| clubs6 = [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan)\n| clubs8 = [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]]\n| clubs9 = \u2192 [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] (loan)\n| clubs10 = [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]]\n| caps1 = 38\n| caps2 = 5\n| caps3 = 12\n| caps4 = 41\n| caps5 = 12\n| caps6 = 45\n| caps7 = 4\n| caps8 = 28\n| caps9 = 9\n| caps10 = 58\n| goals1 = 3\n| goals2 = 1\n| goals3 = 4\n| goals4 = 14\n| goals5 = 4\n| goals6 = 7\n| goals7 = 2\n| goals8 = 5\n| goals9 = 2\n| goals10 = 12\n| totalcaps = 264\n| totalgoals = 54\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 =\n| nationalcaps1 =\n| nationalgoals1 =\n| club-update = 20:49, 27 April 2009 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Michael Anthony Proctor''' (born 3 October 1980) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Sunderland===\nBorn in [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]], [[Tyne and Wear]], Proctor started his career with his hometown club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in their [[youth system]] and signed a professional contract with them on 29 October 1997.<ref name=\"Hugman2008-09\"/> He made his [[first team]] debut for Sunderland against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] on 11 November 1998, which finished as a 1\u20131 draw.<ref name=\"Michael Proctor 1998-99\">{{cite web\n| title = Michael Proctor\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=128&playerid=14789\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref> He was loaned to [[Denmark|Danish]] side [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]] in 2000 to recuperate from a cruciate ligament injury.<ref name=\"Michael Proctor\">{{cite web\n| title = Michael Proctor\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=14789\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Proctor set to apply lower league lessons in higher academy\n |url        = http://sport.independent.co.uk/football/coca_cola/article124130.ece\n |publisher  = The Independent on Sunday\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n |date       = 11 January 2003\n |first      = Tim\n |last       = Rice\n |location   = London\n}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He joined [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] on loan in March 2001, making his debut against [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]], in which he scored in a 4\u20132 win.<ref name=\"Michael Proctor 2000-01\">{{cite web\n| title = Michael Proctor\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=130&playerid=14789\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref> He finished this loan spell with four goals in 12 appearances.<ref name=\"Michael Proctor\"/> He played at [[York City F.C.|York City]] on loan during the [[2001-02 in English football|2001\u201302]] season, making his debut in a 1\u20130 defeat against [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]].<ref name=\"Michael Proctor 2001-02\">{{cite web\n| title = Michael Proctor\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=131&playerid=14789\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref> He finished this spell with 49 appearances and 14 goals, making him York's top scorer for the season.<ref name=\"York 2001/2002 player appearances\">{{cite web\n| title = York 2001/2002 player appearances\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/squad_season.sd?seasonid=131&teamid=2910\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref> He joined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on loan in August 2002.<ref name=\"Law brings in Sunderland striker on loan\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Law brings in Sunderland striker on loan\n| url = http://www.bradfordcityfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10266~260858,00.html\n| publisher = Bradford City AFC\n| date = 17 November 2004\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He scored the winning goal on his debut as Bradford defeated [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] 2\u20131,<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Striker set for longer stay\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/8/28/122548.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130505155640/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/8/28/122548.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 28 August 2002\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref> and became a favourite among fans,<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Mauled by Black Cats\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2003/12/27/104558.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130505082355/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2003/12/27/104558.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 27 December 2003\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref> players,<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = We need to keep Proctor \u2013 Danny\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/10/15/120645.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130505063457/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/10/15/120645.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 15 October 2002\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref> and the board.<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Gibb rules out being City's loan arranger\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2003/10/25/106399.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130505154544/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2003/10/25/106399.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 25 October 2002\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref> He scored a total of four goals in 12 games during his two-month spell, including a late equaliser as nine-man City drew 2\u20132 with [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]],<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Proctor pulls off great escape\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/9/21/121515.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130421105459/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/9/21/121515.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 21 April 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 21 September 2002\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref> but he returned to Sunderland when manager [[Howard Wilkinson]] blocked another month's extension to the loan.<ref>{{cite news\n |title      = Law to replace Proctor\n |url        = http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/10/26/120153.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130505083928/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/10/26/120153.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |publisher  = Telegraph & Argus\n |date       = 26 October 2002\n |accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nHe scored the winner for Sunderland in their 2\u20131 win over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 15 December 2002.<ref name=\"Liverpool impersonate a crisis\">{{cite news\n| title = Liverpool impersonate a crisis\n| url = http://football.guardian.co.uk/Match_Report/0,,-40826,00.html\n| publisher = Guardian Unlimited\n| date = 16 December 2002\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008\n| location=London\n| first=David\n| last=Hopps}}</ref> One unfortunate claim to fame occurred whilst playing for Sunderland in 2003, in a 3\u20131 defeat to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], where Proctor scored two own goals within just five minutes.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Proctor gifts Addicks win\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2395397/Charlton-enjoy-own-goal-feast.html\n|publisher=BBC Sport\n|accessdate=20 January 2008\n|date=1 February 2003}}</ref>\n\n===Rotherham United and Hartlepool United===\nProctor left Sunderland in February 2004, joining [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] in a swap deal for [[Darren Byfield]].<ref name=\"- One In & One Out\">\n{{cite news\n| title = \u2013 One In & One Out\n| url = http://www.themillers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10360~484135,00.html\n| publisher = Rotherham United FC\n| date = 6 February 2004\n| accessdate = 20 January 2008\n}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> He joined [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on a month's loan deal in February 2005.<ref name=\"Swindon sign Proctor on loan deal\">{{cite news\n| title = Swindon sign Proctor on loan deal\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/swindon_town/4287923.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 22 February 2005\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> Swindon could not afford to extend his loan at the club and he returned to Rotherham in March.<ref name=\"Proctor returns after loan spell\">{{cite news\n| title = Proctor returns after loan spell\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rotherham_utd/4369031.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 21 March 2005\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> He later moved to [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] on a free transfer in July 2005.<ref name=\"Hartlepool sign striker Proctor\">{{cite news\n| title = Hartlepool sign striker Proctor\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hartlepool_united/4673225.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 11 July 2005\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> He was best remembered by Hartlepool fans for scoring twice in a 3\u20131 over local rivals [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] in a [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] tie early in his Pools' career.<ref name=\"hartlepool\">{{cite news\n|title=Pools stalk Stag\n|url=http://www.hartlepoolmail.co.uk/sport/Pools-stalk-Stag.2895092.jp\n|publisher=Hartlepool Mail\n|date=22 May 2007\n|accessdate=20 January 2008\n|first=Richard\n|last=Watts}}</ref> He played just 32 games in two seasons for Hartlepool, scoring ten goals, before he was one of ten players released by [[Danny Wilson (footballer, born 1960)|Danny Wilson]].<ref name=\"hartlepool\"/>\n\n===Wrexham===\nProctor joined [[Football League Two|League Two]] club [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] on a month's loan in March 2007.<ref name=\"Wrexham swoop for striker Proctor\">{{cite news\n| title = Wrexham swoop for striker Proctor\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wrexham/6457765.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 23 March 2007\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> This loan was extended until the end of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307]] season in April.<ref name=\"Proctor to stay on with Wrexham\">{{cite news\n| title = Proctor to stay on with Wrexham\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wrexham/6596603.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 26 April 2007\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> During this spell he scored two vital goals for Wrexham in their eventually successful survival bid. These were the winning goal in the 1\u20130 victory at local rivals [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] and the third goal in the Welsh club's 3\u20131 victory over [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] which preserved the club's [[The Football League|Football League]] status. He was released by Hartlepool in May 2007 and expressed an interest in joining Wrexham permanently.<ref name=\"Pools boss Wilson swings his axe\">{{cite news\n| title = Pools boss Wilson swings his axe\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hartlepool_united/6640219.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 9 May 2007\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |title       = Proctor signs three-year deal\n |url         = http://www.dailypost.co.uk/src/webroot/dailypost/sport-news/wrexham-fc/2007/05/22/proctor-signs-three-year-deal-50142-19151008/\n |publisher   = Daily Post\n |date        = 22 May 2007\n |accessdate  = 20 January 2008\n |first       = Mark\n |last        = Currie\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110720012235/http://www.dailypost.co.uk/src/webroot/dailypost/sport-news/wrexham-fc/2007/05/22/proctor-signs-three-year-deal-50142-19151008/\n |archivedate = 20 July 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> This move was confirmed in May 2007.<ref name=\"Wrexham complete Proctor capture\">{{cite news\n| title = Wrexham complete Proctor capture\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wrexham/6677211.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 21 May 2007\n| accessdate = 18 August 2007}}</ref> He was transfer listed by Wrexham in May 2008 following the club's relegation to the [[Football Conference]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wrexham/7367679.stm|title=Roberts and Llewellyn leave Reds |date=6 May 2008|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 May 2008}}</ref> despite finishing the season as the club's top scorer with 12 goals.<ref name=\"Wrexham 2007/2008 player appearances\">{{cite web\n| title = Wrexham 2007/2008 player appearances\n| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/squad_season.sd?seasonid=137&teamid=2859\n| publisher = Soccerbase\n| accessdate = 7 July 2008}}</ref> In the summer of 2009 after talks with manager Dean Saunders, Proctor left the club by mutual consent.\n\n===Media Work===\n\nFrom the start of the 2014/15 season, Michael began to work as a co-host for [[Sun FM]]'s Into The Light football show, discussing all things [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] with the immensely talented duo of Stephen Goldsmith and Gareth Barker of Wise Men Say podcast fame. They arguably carried the show with Michael adding expert opinion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sun-fm.com/of-into-the-light-with-michael-proctor-.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607022640/http://www.sun-fm.com/of-into-the-light-with-michael-proctor-.php |archive-date=7 June 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This isn't an area of work Michael had intentionally planned on getting into after retiring, as he had previously been involved in coaching at East Durham College.<ref>http://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2015/june/where-are-they-now-michael-proctor</ref><ref>http://www.eastdurham.ac.uk/college_student_advances_to_next_round_of_bcs_trials</ref> Since becoming a frequent visitor to the Stadium of Light to undergo his media duties, Michael has begun to work closer with the [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] media team, most notably interviewing [[Jermain Defoe]] about his winning goal in a game against fierce rivals [[Newcastle United]].<ref>http://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2015/april/youtube-jermain-defoe-on-derby-goal</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Michael Proctor}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Proctor, Michael}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sunderland, Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hvidovre IF players]]\n[[Category:Halifax Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:York City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rotherham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hartlepool United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Wrexham A.F.C. players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Proctor_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Smeaton House", "text_new": "'''Smeaton House''', also known as Smeaton Castle, and now as Dalkeith Home Farm,<ref name=ScotlandsPlaces>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotlandsplaces.gov.uk/search_item/index.php?service=RCAHMS&id=53473|title=Smeaton House|work=ScotlandsPlaces|accessdate=2010-01-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719234233/http://www.scotlandsplaces.gov.uk/search_item/index.php?service=RCAHMS&id=53473|archivedate=2011-07-19}}</ref>  is a [[courtyard]] [[castle]] dating from the fifteenth century, about {{convert|2|mi|km}} north of [[Dalkeith]], and {{convert|1|mi|km}} south of [[Inveresk]] in [[East Lothian]], [[Scotland]].<ref name=Coventry>Coventry, Martin (2001) ''The Castles of Scotland''. Goblinshead. {{ISBN|1-899874-26-7}} p.379</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1450 the lands on which Smeaton Castle are built were the property of the [[Abbey]] of [[Dunfermline]].  Thereafter they passed to the Richardsons.  The buildings now form part of a farm.<ref name=Coventry/>\n\n[[Robert Richardson (Lord Treasurer)|Robert Richardson]] (d. 1578) was [[treasurer of Scotland]], and was said to have built a new house at Smeaton in 1577. He raised money for [[Regent Moray]] by pawning the personal jewellery of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], which his son James Richardson returned to [[Regent Morton]].<ref>''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland'', iii, 366: ''Accounts of the Treasurer of Scotland'', xii, 382: ''Accounts of the Treasurer of Scotland'', xiii, 283.</ref>\n\n[[Archibald Douglas, 8th Earl of Angus]] died at Smeaton on 4 August 1588. His illness was attributed to witchcraft and [[North Berwick witch trials|Barbara Napier]] and [[Euphame MacCalzean]] were accused.<ref>David Reid, ''David Hume of Godscroft's History of the House of Angus'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 2005), p. 396-8: ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1589-1603'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 497.</ref>\n\nIn the 1590s [[James VI of Scotland]] and [[Anne of Denmark]] frequently stayed nearby at [[Dalkeith Palace]], and Anne sometimes dined at Smeaton, as she did on 8 August 1598.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/manudavidmilneho00greauoft/page/66/mode/2up ''HMC Report on the Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne Home of Wedderburn Castle'', (London, 1902), p. 71.]</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe castle courtyard had rounded towers, but only two remain standing, with the curtain wall between them.<ref name=Coventry/> These are the two western towers.<ref name=ScotlandsPlaces/>    While one tower has been reduced in height the other remains at four storeys, with an adjoining square stair-tower.<ref name=Coventry/>\n\nOne range of buildings also survives, but considerably changed.  It has a vaulted basement.\n\nThere are traces of a moat.<ref name=ScotlandsPlaces/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://canmore.org.uk/site/53473/smeaton-house Smeaton House, HES/RCAHMS Canmore]\n\n{{coord|55.9159|-3.0451|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Castles in East Lothian]]\n[[Category:Musselburgh]]\n", "text_old": "'''Smeaton House''', also known as Smeaton Castle, and now as Dalkeith Home Farm,<ref name=ScotlandsPlaces>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotlandsplaces.gov.uk/search_item/index.php?service=RCAHMS&id=53473|title=Smeaton House|work=ScotlandsPlaces|accessdate=2010-01-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719234233/http://www.scotlandsplaces.gov.uk/search_item/index.php?service=RCAHMS&id=53473|archivedate=2011-07-19}}</ref>  is a [[courtyard]] [[castle]] dating from the fifteenth century, about {{convert|2|mi|km}} north of [[Dalkeith]], and {{convert|1|mi|km}} south of [[Inveresk]] in [[East Lothian]], [[Scotland]].<ref name=Coventry>Coventry, Martin (2001) ''The Castles of Scotland''. Goblinshead. {{ISBN|1-899874-26-7}} p.379</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1450 the lands on which Smeaton Castle are built were the property of the [[Abbey]] of [[Dunfermline]].  Thereafter they passed to the Richardsons.  The buildings now form part of a farm.<ref name=Coventry/>\n\n[[Robert Richardson (Lord Treasurer)|Robert Richardson]] (d. 1578) was [[treasurer of Scotland]], and was said to have built a new house at Smeaton in 1577. He raised money for [[Regent Moray]] by pawning the personal jewellery of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], which his son James Richardson returned to [[Regent Morton]].<ref>''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland'', iii, 366: ''Accounts of the Treasurer of Scotland'', xii, 382: ''Accounts of the Treasurer of Scotland'', xiii, 283.</ref>\n\n[[Archibald Douglas, 8th Earl of Angus]] died at Smeaton on 4 August 1588. His illness was attributed to witchcraft and [[North Berwick witch trials|Barbara Napier]] was accused.<ref>David Reid, ''David Hume of Godscroft's History of the House of Angus'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 2005), p. 396-8.</ref>\n\nIn the 1590s [[James VI of Scotland]] and [[Anne of Denmark]] frequently stayed nearby at [[Dalkeith Palace]], and Anne sometimes dined at Smeaton, as she did on 8 August 1598.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/manudavidmilneho00greauoft/page/66/mode/2up ''HMC Report on the Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne Home of Wedderburn Castle'', (London, 1902), p. 71.]</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe castle courtyard had rounded towers, but only two remain standing, with the curtain wall between them.<ref name=Coventry/> These are the two western towers.<ref name=ScotlandsPlaces/>    While one tower has been reduced in height the other remains at four storeys, with an adjoining square stair-tower.<ref name=Coventry/>\n\nOne range of buildings also survives, but considerably changed.  It has a vaulted basement.\n\nThere are traces of a moat.<ref name=ScotlandsPlaces/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://canmore.org.uk/site/53473/smeaton-house Smeaton House, HES/RCAHMS Canmore]\n\n{{coord|55.9159|-3.0451|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Castles in East Lothian]]\n[[Category:Musselburgh]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smeaton_House"}
{"title_page": "Michael Nelson (footballer)", "text_new": "{{lead too short|date=October 2013}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Michael Nelson\n| image          = Nelson, Michael.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = Nelson in 2008\n| fullname       = Michael John Nelson<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/staticFiles/4e/bd/0,,10794~179534,00.pdf |format=PDF |page=55 |title=Professional retain lists & free transfers 2012/13 |publisher=The Football League |date=May 2013 |accessdate=18 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802074454/http://www.football-league.co.uk/staticFiles/4e/bd/0%2C%2C10794~179534%2C00.pdf |archivedate=2 August 2014 }}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1980|3|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Gateshead]], England\n| height         = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub    = [[Blyth Spartans A.F.C.|Blyth Spartans]] (player-manager)\n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    =\n| youthclubs1    =\n| years1 = 2000\u20132001 |clubs1 = [[Bishop Auckland F.C.|Bishop Auckland]]     |caps1 = 46 |goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2001\u20132003 |clubs2 = [[Bury F.C.|Bury]]                           |caps2 = 72 |goals2 = 8\n| years3 = 2003\u20132009 |clubs3 = [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] |caps3 = 259 |goals3 =14\n| years4 = 2009\u20132011 |clubs4 = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]           |caps4 = 39 |goals4 = 5\n| years5 = 2011\u20132012 |clubs5 = [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] |caps5 = 30 |goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2012\u20132013 |clubs6 = [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]               |caps6 = 36 |goals6 = 2\n| years7 = 2013      |clubs7 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]       |caps7 = 14 |goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2013\u20132014 |clubs8 = [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]                 |caps8 = 35 |goals8 = 2\n| years9 = 2014\u20132015 |clubs9 = [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]]   |caps9 = 33 |goals9 = 3\n| years10 = 2015\u20132018 |clubs10 = [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]                     |caps10 = 97 |goals10 = 2\n| years11 = 2018\u20132019 |clubs11 = [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]]         |caps11 = 13 |goals11 = 0\n| years12 = 2019\u20132020 |clubs12 = [[Gateshead F.C.|Gateshead]]               |caps12 = 10 |goals12 = 1\n| years13 = 2020\u2013 |clubs13 = [[Blyth Spartans A.F.C.|Blyth Spartans]]         |caps13 = 0  |goals13 = 0\n| totalcaps = 644\n| totalgoals = 38\n| manageryears1 = 2020-\n| managerclubs1 = [[Blyth Spartans A.F.C.|Blyth Spartans]]\n\n}}\n'''Michael John Nelson''' (born 23 March 1980) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] and is currently player-manager at [[Blyth Spartans A.F.C.|Blyth Spartans]]. Nelson has previously played for [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]], [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], [[Bury F.C.|Bury]], [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]], [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]], [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]], [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] and [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nBorn in [[Gateshead]], [[Tyne and Wear]], Nelson started his playing career as a semi-professional, playing for [[non-League football|non-League]] teams such as [[Spennymoor United F.C.|Spennymoor United]], [[Leek Town F.C.|Leek Town]] and [[Bishop Auckland F.C.|Bishop Auckland]]. Nelson's performances attracted the attention of league clubs who sent scouts to watch him. Nelson was given a trial at [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool]] but he was not offered a contract by the then Hartlepool manager [[Chris Turner (footballer b. 1958)|Chris Turner]]. However Nelson was offered a contract at [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] by manager [[Andy Preece]] after Bury scout Peter Ward convinced him to give Nelson a chance.\n\n===Bury===\nOnce Nelson had settled down to professional football, he gradually became a first team regular and during his first full season at Bury he managed to play 31 of the clubs 46 league matches, scoring 2 goals in the process. Nelson formed a defensive partnership with [[Danny Swailes]]. However, during the season Nelson suffered what he described as ''the worst injury of his career'' after suffering a collapsed lung and several cracked ribs after a collision during Bury's match against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]. Nelson had to have a drain inserted into his chest for several days while he was hospitalised. The injury threatened to keep him sidelined for three months but remarkably Nelson was able to resume training less than three weeks later.\n\nDespite being dropped early on, Nelson's second season turned out to be even more successful as he played in 40 of Bury's 46 matches, scoring 5 goals. Nelson was made club captain and his performances earned him the respect of the club's players and fans. During that season, Bury manager Andy Preece hailed Nelson as \"the best centre-half in Division Three\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchesteronline.co.uk/sport/football/bury/s/58/58059_nelsons_different_class.html|title=Nelson's different class|date=8 May 2003|publisher=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=18 April 2010}}</ref> However, Bury failed to gain promotion to League 1 as they missed out during the play-offs and Nelson was offered the chance to play in a higher division by several League 1 clubs.\n\n===Hartlepool United===\nThe following season, Nelson joined Hartlepool United on the same day that [[Neale Cooper]] was appointed manager for a fee of around \u00a370,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nelson sails into Hartlepool|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11756/2269095/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=26 June 2003|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> Nelson was seen as natural replacement for [[Graeme Lee (footballer)|Graeme Lee]] who had joined Sheffield Wednesday. Nelson started strongly for Hartlepool and scored the winner from 30 yards during his debut in Hartlepool's 4\u20133 win over [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough]]. This goal almost earned him another award as it was on the shortlist for Hartlepool's Goal of the Season. He was also voted September's Player of the Month on the official Hartlepool website. Nelson began to form a strong partnership with [[Chris Westwood]] and the pair played together for the majority of Hartlepool's games. Nelson went on to play in 40 of Hartlepool's league matches and played in both legs of Hartlepool's play-off semi-final match against [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]. Nelson was in contention for Hartlepool's Fans and Players' Player of the season but he missed out to [[Jim Provett]] on both occasions.\n\nHowever Nelson failed to maintain this through to the 2004\u201305 season and he handed in a transfer request.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nelson asks for transfer|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11756/2314645/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=25 October 2004|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> His agent claimed that he'd been \"promised\" a better deal. This triggered a feud with Hartlepool chairman [[Ken Hodcroft]] who criticised Nelson and his agent. Nelson was missing in several of Hartlepool's matches and was rumoured to be signing for [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] for a fee of around \u00a3100,000. However Nelson withdrew his transfer request and was reinstalled into the starting line-up. His performances earned him an improved contract and he was offered a new three-year contract that would tie him to the club until 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nelson stays with Pools|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11756/2341528/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=9 July 2005|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nNelson's third season of the club saw him receiving his first red card for Hartlepool after he retaliated and elbowed [[Jack Lester]] during Hartlepool's defeat to Nottingham Forest. He was the favoured central defender alongside [[Ben Clark (footballer born 1983)|Ben Clark]] during the [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]] campaign, playing a major part in the 18 game unbeaten run along with [[Dimitrios Konstantopoulos]] in goal. The season also saw him take the captain's armband in the absence on [[Michael Barron]].\n\nNelson was named in the PFA [[Football League Two|League Two]] Team of the Year for the 2006\u201307 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6582201.stm|title=Ronaldo secures PFA awards double |publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 April 2010 | date=22 April 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Norwich City===\nIn June 2009, Nelson agreed to join [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], who had just been relegated to [[Football League One|League One]], on a two-year deal once his contract at Hartlepool expired at the end of the month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~1696213,00.html|title=Nelson set to join|date=19 June 2009|publisher=Norwich City F.C|accessdate=18 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627043549/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~1696213,00.html|archivedate=27 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He made his debut in the 7\u20131 opening-day thrashing at the hands of Colchester, and did not play for the first team again until the game against his former club Hartlepool later in August, in which he scored a magnificent overhead kick. It was his first goal for Norwich and put the Canaries on course for a 2\u20130 win at Victoria Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10355~47377,00.html|title=Hartlepool vs Norwich|date=29 August 2009|publisher=Norwich City F.C|accessdate=18 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091004063238/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10355~47377,00.html|archivedate=4 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Nelson established himself as a regular starter following an injury to teammate [[Jens Berthel Askou]] in December. He subsequently formed a strong central defensive partnership with Gary Doherty as Norwich surged up the League One table, overhauling runaway leaders Leeds United in the process. On 17 April 2010, he scored the only goal in a 1\u20130 victory at [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] which secured Norwich's return to the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] at the first attempt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/8617895.stm|title=Charlton 0\u20131 Norwich|date=17 April 2010|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 April 2010}}</ref> Nelson's scored his third goal for Norwich in a 2\u20130 win over Gillingham.<ref>{{cite news |title=Norwich City vs Gillingham |url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10355~49056,00.html |work=canaries.co.uk |publisher=Norwich City F.C. |date=24 April 2010 |accessdate=24 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909140624/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10355~49056,00.html |archivedate=9 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In his second season, Nelson scored his fourth goal against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] in a 3\u20132 loss in Norwich City's first match of the season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Norwich City vs Watford |url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10355~52634,00.html |work=canaries.co.uk |publisher=Norwich City F.C. |date=6 August 2010 |accessdate=6 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100823002449/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10355~52634,00.html |archivedate=23 August 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Nelson scored his fifth and last goal for Norwich against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in a 4\u20132 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Norwich City vs Sheffield Utd |url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10355~52025,00.html |work=canaries.co.uk |publisher=Norwich City F.C. |date=28 December 2010 |accessdate=28 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424021158/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10355~52025,00.html |archivedate=24 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Nelson remained in the first team for Norwich City until he suffered a foot injury. Following his return from injury, Nelson was targeting the first team but was deemed surplus to requirements by Canaries boss Paul Lambert as Lambert favoured [[Elliott Ward]] and [[Leon Barnett]] as their first choice centre back. Nelson is held in very high esteem by Norwich City fans for his performances during the successful League One campaign. He received a standing ovation from Carrow Road on his return with new club Scunthorpe United.\n\n===Scunthorpe United===\nHe left the Canaries on deadline day in January 2011 for an undisclosed fee, joining Scunthorpe United, just an hour from the deadline.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nelson makes Iron move |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/6715516/ |work=Sky Sports |publisher=BSkyB |date=1 February 2011 |accessdate=1 February 2011 }}</ref> Nelson made his debut for Scunthorpe United in a disastrous 5\u20131 defeat to Hull City.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scunthorpe United 1\u20135 Hull City |url=http://www.scunthorpe-united.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10442~53499,00.html |work=scunthorpe-united.co.uk |publisher=[[Scunthorpe United F.C.]] |date=5 February 2011 |accessdate=5 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110212144626/http://www.scunthorpe-united.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10442~53499,00.html |archivedate=12 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> At the end of the season, Scunthorpe were relegated to League One. Nelson scored his first goal for Scunthorpe in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wycombe Wanderers 1\u20131 Scunthorpe United |url=http://www.scunthorpe-united.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10442~58452,00.html |work=scunthorpe-united.co.uk |publisher=[[Scunthorpe United F.C.]] |date=6 August 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2011 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Scunthorpe's poor form continued and at the end of 2011 the club was just above the relegation zone to League Two. In January 2012, Nelson was strongly linked with move away from Scunthorpe following a restructuring programme at the club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nelson set for Iron exit |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12691/7413039/Nelson-set-for-Iron-exit |work=Sky Sports |publisher=BSkyB |date=5 January 2012 |accessdate=5 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Kilmarnock===\nOn 14 January 2012, Nelson signed for Scottish Premier League side [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], a two-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shiels delight at Nelson deal |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/7429201/ |work=Sky Sports |publisher=BSkyB |date=14 January 2012|accessdate=15 January 2012 }}</ref> After the move, Manager [[Kenny Shiels]] described new signing Nelson as 'quality' and expected Nelson will be good asset in the second half of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shiels delight at Nelson deal|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/7429201/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=14 January 2012|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> Shortly joining, Nelson revealed that then Norwich City manager [[Paul Lambert]] made a recommendation of Nelson joining Kilmarnock.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Nelson thanks Paul Lambert for Kilmarnock move|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16865425|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2012|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> Nelson had to wait until on 4 February 2012 when he made his debut, playing in the central defence, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]]. Then on 18 March, he played in the [[2012 Scottish League Cup Final]] which Kilmarnock won after beating [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news\n | url =  https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17330246\n | title =  Celtic 0\u20131 Kilmarnock\n | publisher =   BBC Sport\n | date =   18 March 2012\n | accessdate = 19 March 2012}}</ref> A week after the Scottish League Cup Final, Nelson scored his first goal for the club in a 4\u20133 thriller victory over [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Kilmarnock 4\u20133 Inverness CT|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17795315|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 April 2012|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> The next season, Nelson continued to retain his first team place until he left and start his new season when he scored his first goal in the second round of Scottish League Cup, in a 2\u20131 loss against [[Stenhousemuir F.C.|Stenhousemuir]] and he soon scored his second goal for the club in a 2\u20131 loss against [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] on 24 November 2012.\n\n===Bradford City===\n[[File:Michael Nelson 1.png|thumb|200px|Nelson with the victory parade that followed [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]'s victory in the [[2013 Football League Two play-off Final]]]]\nOn 15 January 2013, Nelson agreed to join [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on an 18-month deal for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21045312 |title=Bradford City sign Kilmarnock's Michael Nelson|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref> Thirty days later, on 15 February 2013, when asked why Nelson was sold, Shiels then explained his decision selling Nelson, that he wanted to be close with his children and described his departure as a \"big loss\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Q&A: Kilmarnock boss Kenny Shiels|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21451688|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 February 2013|accessdate=9 June 2013}}</ref> He made his debut on 2 February, in a 2\u20132 draw away to [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21209109 \"Fleetwood 2\u20132 Bradford\"] BBC Sport. 2 February 2013. Retrieved 17 February 2013.</ref> Nelson was an unused substitute as Bradford won promotion to [[Football League One|League One]] by winning the [[2013 Football League Two play-off Final]].\n\n===Hibernian===\nOn 1 August 2013 Nelson signed a two-year deal with [[Scottish Premiership]] side [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]], moving from Bradford City for a nominal transfer fee. He had then left the club after agreeing mutual termination of his contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nelson Joins Hibernian|url=http://www.hibernianfc.co.uk/news/20130801/nelson-joins-hibernian_2262950_3334559|publisher=Hibernian F.C.|date=1 August 2013|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Cambridge United===\nOn 26 August 2014 Nelson signed a one-year contract with [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] shortly after agreeing mutual termination with his previous club [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]].<ref>{{cite news|title=U'S SECURE NELSON SIGNING|url=http://www.cambridge-united.co.uk/news/article/michael-nelson-signs-for-cambridge-united-1870538.aspx|publisher=Cambridge United|date=27 August 2014}}</ref> At the end of the 2014\u201315 season the club did not offer him a new deal when his contract expired.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cambridge-united.co.uk/news/article/us-retained-list-confirmed-2442891.aspx|title=U's retained list confirmed|publisher=Cambridge United|date=6 May 2015|accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Barnet===\nNelson joined [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] on trial in 2015\u201316 pre-season, and signed a one-year deal on 3 August.<ref>[http://www.barnetfc.com/news/article/michael-nelson-signs-for-the-bees-2590034.aspx Michael Nelson signs for the Bees!]</ref> Nelson signed a new deal at the end of the season and extended his contract into a third year in summer 2017, also taking up a role as the club's under-23 team coach.<ref>[https://www.barnetfc.com/news/2017/june/nelson-signs-new-deal/ Breaking: Michael Nelson signs new contract with Barnet]</ref> Following the appointment of [[Graham Westley]] as head coach, Nelson was appointed as his assistant for the first team,<ref>[https://www.barnetfc.com/news/2018/january/news--michael-nelson-confirmed-as-new-assistant-coach/ News | Michael Nelson confirmed as new Assistant Coach]</ref> but returned to playing duties following the appointment of [[Martin Allen]].\n\nBarnet claimed to have offered Nelson a new contract at the end of the 2017\u201318 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44039230|title=John Akinde: Barnet put striker on transfer list after relegation to National League|date=8 May 2018|accessdate=10 May 2018|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> but this was disputed by the player himself.<ref>[https://twitter.com/mnelse6/status/999052930467721223 michael nelson on Twitter: \"Gaffa wanted me to sign a new deal & told the club that. He left a few days later. I contacted the club on 12th May & have had no contact since, ev...<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Chesterfield===\nNelson signed a one-year deal with [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] on 22 May 2018. Manager [[Martin Allen (footballer)|Martin Allen]] said \"Michael is very old with great experience and good knowledge. He is a leader of men and he knows how to win games. He is as fit as a butcher's dog and he is a great man to work with.\"<ref>[https://www.chesterfield-fc.co.uk/news/2018/may/20180522-third-deal-today-completed/ Third Deal Completed]</ref>\n\n===Gateshead===\nIn the summer of 2019, Nelson signed for his home town club, [[Gateshead F.C.|Gateshead]], as a player-coach;<ref>[https://www.gateshead-fc.com/teams/229141/coach/michael-nelson-1373210 Michael Nelson - Gateshead FC First Team<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> he made his d\u00e9but in a 0\u20130 draw at [[A.F.C. Telford United]] on 10 August.<ref>[https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2019/08/10/england/conference-n--s/afc-telford-united/gateshead-fc/3054509/ AFC Telford United vs. Gateshead - 10 August 2019 - Soccerway<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Stevenage===\nNelson was appointed assistant manager of [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] on 17 January 2020, once again assisting [[Graham Westley]].<ref>[https://www.stevenagefc.com/news/2020/january/michael-nelson-stevenage-football-club-assistant-coaching-staff-friday-17th-january-2020/ Michael Nelson Appointed To Coaching Staff]</ref> Nelson left the club a month later after [[Alex Revell]] was appointed manager.<ref>[https://www.stevenagefc.com/news/2020/february/russell-slade-stevenage-football-club-management-team-news-sky-bet-league-two-efl-english-football-league-monday-17th-february-2020/ Russell Slade brought in as Managerial Consultant]</ref>\n\n===Blyth Spartans===\nNelson returned to playing when he joined [[Blyth Spartans A.F.C.|Blyth Spartans]] on 26 February 2020 until the end of the season.<ref>[http://www.blythspartans.com/arrival-experienced-defender-nelson-joins-blyth/ Arrival | Experienced defender Nelson joins Blyth]</ref> A week later Nelson was then made player-manager after the departure of [[Lee Clark (footballer)|Lee Clark]].\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 14 September 2019}}<ref>{{soccerbase|id=24581}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Bury F.C.|Bury]]\n|[[2000\u201301 Bury F.C. season|2000\u201301]]\n|[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]\n|2||1||0||0||0||0||0||0||2||1\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 Bury F.C. season|2001\u201302]]\n|Seco