r= }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline|Lunds domkyrka|Lund Cathedral}}\n* [https://lundsdomkyrka.se/ Official website of the cathedral]\n* [http://www.alvin-portal.org/alvin/view.jsf?pid=alvin-record%3A14714&dswid=3243 Digitised copy of the ''Necrologium Lundense'', with information about the book and its contents in English]\n* [http://www.alvin-portal.org/alvin/view.jsf?pid=alvin-record%3A13276&dswid=7054 Digitised copy of the ''Liber daticus vetustior'', with information about the book and its contents in English]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC3LzcTh1FX5k3C8Y4EJI0Ew YouTube channel of the cathedral]\n\n{{Churches in Scania}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1145]]\n[[Category:12th-century churches]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lund]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic cathedrals in pre-Reformation Sweden]]\n[[Category:Lutheran cathedrals in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Romanesque architecture in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Lund]]\n[[Category:Coronation church buildings]]\n[[Category:Churches in Sk\u00e5ne County]]\n[[Category:Churches in the Diocese of Lund]]\n", "name_user": "CaroleHenson", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lund_Cathedral"}
{"title_page": "Nova Scotia Trunk 22", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|province= NS\n|type= Trunk\n|route= 22\n|alternate_name=Mira Road\n|length_km=35.6\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"gmaps\">{{google maps |title=Nova Scotia Trunk 22 |url=https://www.google.ca/maps/@46.0243784,-60.0651243,11.42z |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n|direction_a=North\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=NS|Trunk|4}} in [[Sydney, Nova Scotia|Sydney]]\n|junction={{jct|state=NS|Hwy|125}} in [[Sydney, Nova Scotia|Sydney]]\n|direction_b=South\n|terminus_b=[[Louisbourg]]\n|municipalities=[[Cape Breton Regional Municipality]]\n|towns= \n|cities=\n|previous_type= Trunk\n|previous_route= 19\n|next_type= Trunk\n|next_route=28\n}}\n'''Trunk 22''' is part of the [[Canada|Canadian]] province of [[Nova Scotia]]'s system of trunk highways. The route runs from [[Sydney, Nova Scotia|Sydney]] to [[Louisbourg]], a distance of {{convert|36|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"gmaps\"/>\n\nTrunk 22, which leaves Sydney to the southeast on George Street, is known over most of its route as the Mira Road. The route crosses the [[Mira River (Nova Scotia)|Mira River]] at [[Albert Bridge, Nova Scotia|Albert Bridge]].<ref name=\"map\">{{cite map |title = Nova Scotia Road Map |year = 2019 |scale = 1:640,000 |publisher = Province of Nova Scotia |sections = D-16, E-16, E-17 |language = en}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{NSinttop|length_ref=<ref name=\"gmaps\"/>|division=Cape Breton Regional Municipality}}\n{{NSint\n|location=Sydney\n|lspan=2\n|km=0.0\n|road={{jctname|state=NS|Trunk|4|name1=Prince Street|city1=Sydney River|city2=St. Peters|city3=Glace Bay}}\n|notes=Northern terminus; Trunk 22 follows George Street\n}}\n{{NSint\n|km=3.3\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Hwy|125|TCH|105|to2=yes|city1=Glace Bay|city2=North Sydney|city3=Baddeck}}\n|notes=Hwy 125 exit 8\n}}\n{{NSint\n|location=Hornes Road\n|km=15.6\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Route|255|dir1=north|city1=Mira Gut}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{Jctbridge|state=NS\n|location=Albert Bridge\n|km=17.4\n|bridge=Crosses the [[Mira River (Nova Scotia)|Mira River]]\n}}\n{{NSint\n|location=Louisbourg\n|km=35.6\n|road=[[Fortress of Louisbourg]] National Historic Site\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{NS Roads and Highways}}\n\n[[Category:Nova Scotia provincial highways|022]]\n[[Category:Roads in the Cape Breton Regional Municipality]]\n\n\n{{NovaScotia-road-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|province= NS\n|type= Trunk\n|route= 22\n|alternate_name=Mira Road\n|length_km=35.6\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"gmaps\">{{google maps |title=Nova Scotia Trunk 22 |url=https://www.google.ca/maps/@46.0243784,-60.0651243,11.42z |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n|direction_a=North\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=NS|Trunk|4}} in [[Sydney, Nova Scotia|Sydney]]\n|junction={{jct|state=NS|Hwy|125}} in [[Sydney, Nova Scotia|Sydney]]\n|direction_b=South\n|terminus_b=[[Louisbourg]]\n|municipalities=[[Cape Breton Regional Municipality]]\n|towns= \n|cities=\n|previous_type= Trunk\n|previous_route= 19\n|next_type= Trunk\n|next_route=28\n}}\n'''Trunk 22''' is part of the [[Canada|Canadian]] province of [[Nova Scotia]]'s system of trunk highways. The route runs from [[Sydney, Nova Scotia|Sydney]] to [[Louisbourg]], a distance of {{convert|36|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"gmaps\"/>\n\nTrunk 22, which leaves Sydney to the southeast on George Street, is known over most of its route as the Mira Road. The route crosses the [[Mira River (Nova Scotia)|Mira River]] at [[Albert Bridge, Nova Scotia|Albert Bridge]].<ref name=\"map\">{{cite map |title = Nova Scotia Road Map |year = 2019 |scale = 1:640,000 |publisher = Province of Nova Scotia |sections = D-16, E-16, E-17 |language = en}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{NSinttop|length_ref=<ref name=\"gmaps\"/>|division=Cape Breton Regional Municipality}}\n{{NSint\n|location=Sydney\n|lspan=2\n|km=0.0\n|road={{jctname|state=NS|Trunk|4|name1=Prince Street|city1=Sydney River|city2=St. Peters|city3=Glace Bay}}\n|notes=Northern terminus; Trunk 22 follows George Street\n}}\n{{NSint\n|km=3.3\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Hwy|125|TCH|105|to2=yes|city1=Glace Bay|city2=North Sydney|city3=Baddeck}}\n|notes=Hwy 125 exit 8\n}}\n{{NSint\n|location=none\n|km=15.6\n|road={{jct|state=NS|Route|255|dir1=north|name1=Hornes Road|city1=Mira Gut}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{Jctbridge|state=NS\n|location=Albert Bridge\n|km=17.4\n|bridge=Crosses the [[Mira River (Nova Scotia)|Mira River]]\n}}\n{{NSint\n|location=Louisbourg\n|km=35.6\n|road=[[Fortress of Louisbourg]] National Historic Site\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{NS Roads and Highways}}\n\n[[Category:Nova Scotia provincial highways|022]]\n[[Category:Roads in the Cape Breton Regional Municipality]]\n\n\n{{NovaScotia-road-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MuzikMachine", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMajor intersections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_Trunk_22"}
{"title_page": "Environmental issues in New York City", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n[[File:Jacqueline_Kennedy_Onassis_Reservoir.jpg|275px|thumb|alt=Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis Reservoir in Central Park|[[Central Park]]'s reservoirs were historically important components of the [[New York City water supply system]].]]\n'''Environmental issues in [[New York City]]''' are  affected by the city's size, density, [[Transportation in New York City|abundant public transportation infrastructure]], and location at the mouth of the [[Hudson River]].\n\nNew York's population density has environmental pros and cons. It facilitates the highest [[mass transit]] use in the United States, but also concentrates pollution. [[Gasoline consumption]] in the city is at the rate the national average was in the 1920s,<ref name=\"New York City energy consumption\" /> and [[greenhouse gas]] emissions are a fraction of the national average, at 7.1 metric tons per person per year, below San Francisco, at 11.2 metric tons, and the national average, at 24.5 metric tons.<ref name=\"NYC emissions\">{{cite news |title=Inventory of New York City Greenhouse Gas Emissions |author=New York City Office of Long-term Planning and Sustainability |date=April 2007 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/om/pdf/ccp_report041007.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=April 11, 2007}}</ref> New York City accounts for only 1% of United States greenhouse gas emissions while housing 2.7% of its population.<ref name=\"NYC emissions\"/>\nIn September 2012, New York was named the #1 \"America's Dirtiest City,\" by a ''[[Travel+Leisure]]'' readership survey that rated the environmental quality of 35 prominent cities in the United States.\n\n==Population density in New York City==\n\nEnvironmental concerns in the city involve managing the city's extraordinary [[population density]].  Mass transit use is the highest in the nation and gasoline consumption in the city is at the rate the national average was in the 1920s.<ref name=\"New York City energy consumption\">{{cite book |first=Ben |last=Jervey |title=The Big Green Apple: Your Guide to Eco-Friendly Living in New York City |isbn=978-0-7627-3835-9 |publisher=Globe Pequot Press |year=2006 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/biggreenappleyou00jerv }}</ref> New York City's dense population and low [[automobile dependence]] help make New York among the most [[energy efficiency in transportation|energy efficient]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |author=Owen, David |title=Green Manhattan |publisher=The New Yorker |date=October 18, 2004}}</ref> The city's greenhouse gas emission levels are relatively low when measured per capita, at 7.1 metric tons per person, below [[San Francisco]], at 11.2 metric tons, and the national average, at 24.5.<ref name=\"NYC emissions\"/>  New Yorkers are collectively responsible for one percent of the nation's total [[greenhouse gas]] emissions,<ref name=\"NYC emissions\"/> though comprise 2.7% of the nation's population.  The average New Yorker consumes less than half the electricity used by a resident of San Francisco and nearly one-quarter the electricity consumed by a resident of [[Dallas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/planyc2030/html/challenge/faq.shtml |title=Global Warming and Greenhouse Gases |publisher=[[PlaNYC]] / The City of New York |date=December 6, 2006 |accessdate=December 13, 2006}}</ref>\n\nConcentrated pollution in New York City leads to high incidence of [[asthma]] and other respiratory conditions among the city's residents.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Urban Asthma and the Neighbourhood Environment  New York City |author1=Coburn, Jason |author2=Jeffrey Osleeb |author3=Michael Porter |journal=Health & Place |date=June 2006 |volume=12 |pages=167\u2013179 |pmid=16338632 |doi=10.1016/j.healthplace.2004.11.002 |issue=2}}</ref>  In recent years the city has focused on reducing its environmental impact. The city government is required to purchase only the most energy-efficient equipment for use in city offices and public housing.<ref>{{cite news |author=DePalma, Anthony |title=It Never Sleeps, but It's Learned to Douse the Lights |publisher=The New York Times |date=December 11, 2005 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/11/nyregion/11efficiency.html |accessdate=July 19, 2006}}</ref> New York has the largest clean air diesel-[[hybrid vehicle|hybrid]] and [[compressed natural gas]] bus fleet in the country, and some of the first hybrid taxis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/nyct/bus/centennial/page2.htm |title=A Century of Buses in New York City |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority |accessdate=November 17, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060525043420/http://mta.info/nyct/bus/centennial/page2.htm |archivedate=July 14, 2016 |url-status=dead }}\n* See also {{cite press release |url=http://www.sierraclub.org/pressroom/releases/pr2005-07-01a.asp |title=New York City\u2019s Yellow Cabs Go Green |publisher=Sierra Club |date=July 1, 2005 |accessdate=July 19, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107223735/http://www.sierraclub.org/pressroom/releases/pr2005-07-01a.asp |archivedate=January 7, 2009 }}</ref> The city is also a leader in the construction of energy-efficient [[green building|green office buildings]], including the [[Hearst Tower (New York City)|Hearst Tower]] among others.<ref name=\"greenbuilding\">{{cite news |title=7 World Trade Center and Hearst Building: New York's Test Cases for Environmentally Aware Office Towers |publisher=The New York Times |date=April 16, 2006 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/16/arts/design/16gree.html |accessdate=July 19, 2006 |author=Pogrebin, Robin |authorlink=Robin Pogrebin}}</ref>\n\nNew York City is supplied with drinking water by the protected [[Catskill Mountains]] [[Drainage basin|watershed]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/maplevels.html |title=Although New york tap water is safe to drink the water quality is not all that impressive and although the city has made efforts to improve the water quality they will never achieve standards set by those cities in asia such as Singapore and hong kong Current Reservoir Levels |publisher=New York City Department of Environmental Protection |accessdate=June 4, 2007}}</ref> As a result of the watershed's integrity and undisturbed natural water filtration process, New York is one of only five major cities in the United States with drinking water pure enough not to require purification by [[water treatment]] plants.<ref>{{cite conference|last=Miele |first=Joel A., Sr |title=Maintaining Water Quality that Satisfies Customers: New York City Watershed Agricultural Program |booktitle=International Water Supply Symposium Tokyo 1998 |publisher=New York City Department of Environmental Protection |date=November 20, 1998 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/news/tokyo2.html |accessdate=November 17, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061012182905/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/news/tokyo2.html |archivedate=October 12, 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New York City 2005 Drinking Water Supply and Quality Report |publisher=New York City Department of Environmental Protection |year=2005 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/pdf/wsstat05.pdf |accessdate=July 17, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Policy and influence==\n[[File:Castelloplan.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Lower Manhattan in 1660, when it was part of [[New Amsterdam]] (Nieuw Amsterdam).]]\n\n{{details|Large Cities Climate Leadership Group}}\n\n{{as of|2005}}, the city has focused on reducing its environmental impact. The city government is required to purchase only the most energy-efficient equipment for use in city offices and public housing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/11/nyregion/11efficiency.html |title=It Never Sleeps, but It's Learned to Douse the Lights |publisher=New York Times |date=December 11, 2005 |accessdate=July 19, 2006 |first=Anthony |last=Depalma}}</ref> New York has the largest clean-air diesel-[[hybrid vehicle|hybrid]] and [[compressed natural gas]] bus fleet in the country, and some of the first hybrid taxis.<ref>\n* Metropolitan Transportation Authority [http://web.mta.info/nyct/bus/centennial/page2.htm Different Buses for Different Jobs] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060525043420/http://mta.info/nyct/bus/centennial/page2.htm |date=May 25, 2006 }}, retrieved on July 14, 2016\n* {{cite news |title=New York City\u2019s Yellow Cabs Go Green |publisher=Sierra Club press release |date=July 1, 2005 |url=http://www.sierraclub.org/pressroom/releases/pr2005-07-01a.asp |accessdate=July 19, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107223735/http://www.sierraclub.org/pressroom/releases/pr2005-07-01a.asp |archivedate=January 7, 2009 }}</ref> The city is also a leader in energy-efficient \"green\" office buildings, such as [[Hearst Tower (New York City)|Hearst Tower]] and [[7 World Trade Center]].<ref name=\"greenbuilding\"/>\n\nEnvironmental groups make large efforts to help shape legislation in New York because they see the strategy as an efficient way to influence national programs. New York City's economy is larger than Switzerland's, a size that means the city has potential to set new ''de facto'' standards. Manufacturers are also attuned to the latest trends and needs in the city because the market is simply too big to ignore.\n\nEx-mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] is one of 248 mayors from 41 states to have signed the U.S. Mayors Climate Protection Agreement. Under the agreement, mayors \"strive to meet or beat the Kyoto Protocol targets in their own communities\". The city was a petitioner in the landmark ''[[Massachusetts v. Environmental Protection Agency]]'' Supreme Court case forcing the EPA to regulate [[greenhouse gases]] as pollutants.\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Energy efficiency==\n{{Bar chart\n| title       = Average annual residential electricity usage by city, 2000-2005<ref>{{cite news |title=New York City's Climate Change Challenges through 2030 |author=New York City Mayor's Office of Sustainability |year=2007 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/planyc2030/downloads/pdf/greenyc_climate-change.pdf |accessdate=February 28, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712134102/http://www.nyc.gov/html/planyc2030/downloads/pdf/greenyc_climate-change.pdf |archive-date=July 12, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| label_type  = City\n| data_type   = per-customer kwh use\n| bar_width   = 300\n| width_units = px\n| data_max    = 17000\n| float       = right\n| label1   = {{hilite|New York City}}\n| data1    = 4696\n| label2   = San Francisco\n| data2    = 6753\n| label3   = Chicago\n| data3    = 8143\n| label4   = Phoenix\n| data4    = 13344\n| label5   = Houston\n| data5    = 14542\n| label6   = Dallas\n| data6    = 16611\n}}\n\nThe city's unique density, encouraged by much of it being surrounded by water, facilitates the highest rate of mass transit use in the United States. New York is one of the most [[Efficient energy use|energy efficient]] cities in the United States as a result. Gasoline consumption in New York is at the rate the national average was in the 1920s.<ref name=\"ny.metro.us\">Jervey, Ben, [http://ny.metro.us/metro/local/article/A_guide_for_perplexed_wouldbe_ecofriends/730.html \"The Big Green Apple: Your Guide to Eco-Friendly Living in New York City\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060626061239/http://ny.metro.us/metro/local/article/A_guide_for_perplexed_wouldbe_ecofriends/730.html |date=June 26, 2006 }}, ''Metro New York''.</ref>  The city's mass transit system, multifamily housing, mixed neighborhoods and the fact that [[greenfield land]] is no longer available to development, make building in New York very energy efficient. New York City has a larger population than all but eleven states, and consumes less energy per-capita than any.<ref>Owen, David, [http://www.greenbelt.org/downloads/resources/newswire_11_04GreenManhattan.pdf \"Green Manhattan]\", ''The New Yorker'', October 18, 2004</ref> The average New Yorker consumes a little more than half of the electricity of someone who lives in Chicago and nearly one-quarter the electricity consumed by someone who lives in Dallas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Warming and Greenhouse Gases |publisher=[[PlaNYC]] |date=December 6, 2006 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/planyc2030/html/about/faq.shtml#warming-6 |accessdate=December 13, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070109085743/http://www.nyc.gov/html/planyc2030/html/about/faq.shtml |archivedate=January 9, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, New York faces growing energy demands and limited space. The city has introduced a series of environmental policies since the 1990s to address these problems. Detailed measures included switching more than 11,000 traffic lights and pedestrian signals in the city to new energy-efficient [[light-emitting diodes]] that use 90% less energy than conventional fixtures. The city replaced 149,000 \"cobra head\" street lights with new energy-efficient designs by 2008. Over 180,000 inefficient refrigerators in public [[New York City Housing Authority|housing projects]] have been replaced with new ones that use a quarter of the power of the old ones. By law, the city government can purchase only the most efficient cars, air-conditioners and copy machines.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/11/nyregion/11efficiency.html \"It Never Sleeps, but It's Learned to Douse the Lights\"], ''The New York Times'', December 11, 2005.</ref>  The electricity used to power the [[Statue of Liberty]], [[Ellis Island]] and 22 other federal buildings in New York City, an annual electricity demand of roughly 27 million kilowatt hours, is provided by wind power.<ref>[http://www.gothamgazette.com/article/environment/20060308/7/1782 \"Wind Power In NYC\"], ''Gotham Gazette'', March 8, 2006.</ref>\n\nNew York City is home to several clean energy projects. Two attempts to provide electricity to [[Roosevelt Island]] by installing underwater turbines in the [[East River]] failed when the turbine blades were torn off by currents. An improved turbine design proved to be successful and on January 23, 2012 [[FERC]] issued a 10-year pilot commercial license to Verdant Power\u2019s RITE Project \u2013 the first commercial license for tidal power in the United States. Under the license, Verdant Power expects to generate up to 1 megawatt after a staged installation of up to 30 turbines. Planning is also underway to construct windmills on a hill in the former [[Fresh Kills Landfill]]. The wind energy project would power 5,000 homes on Staten Island.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\n\n===Transportation===\n\n{{main article|Transportation in New York City}}\n\nNew York is distinguished from other American cities by its extensive use of [[public transportation]]. While nearly 90% of Americans drive to their jobs, public transit is overwhelmingly dominant for New Yorkers.<ref name=\"bts.gov\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bts.gov/publications/highlights_of_the_2001_national_household_travel_survey/html/executive_summary.html |title=Bureau of Transportation Statistics, U.S. Department of Transportation |access-date=August 27, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002070118/http://www.bts.gov/publications/highlights_of_the_2001_national_household_travel_survey/html/executive_summary.html |archive-date=October 2, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> According to the [[United States 2000 Census|2000 U.S. Census]], New York City is the only locality in the United States where more than half of all households do not own a car (the figure is even higher in Manhattan, over 75%; nationally, the rate is 8%).<ref name=\"bts.gov\"/> About one-third of users of mass transit in the United States and two-thirds of the nation's rail riders live in New York and its suburbs, and New York City's public transit system accounts for nearly four times as many passenger miles as the [[Washington, D.C. Metropolitan Area|Washington, D.C.]], and [[Los Angeles metropolitan area|Los Angeles]] metro regions combined.<ref>The Metropolitan Transportation Authority. [http://web.mta.info/mta/network.htm Network]; and David Owens.</ref> Only 6% of shopping trips by New Yorkers involve the use of a car.<ref>[http://www.transalt.org/press/releases/060223necessity_choice.html \"Necessity or Choice? Why People Drive in Manhattan.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060908144835/http://www.transalt.org/press/releases/060223necessity_choice.html |date=September 8, 2006 }} ''[[Transportation Alternatives]]'' Feb 2006.</ref>\n\nNew York City's high rate of transit use saved {{convert|1.8|e9USgal|m3}} of oil in 2006 and $4.6 billion in gasoline costs. New York saves half of all the oil saved by transit nationwide. The reduction in oil consumption meant 11.8 million metric tons of carbon dioxide pollution was kept out of the air.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Better Way to Go: Meeting America's 21st Century Transportation Challenges with Modern Public Transit |publisher=U.S. Public Interest Research Group |date=March 2008 |url=http://www.uspirg.org/uploads/2q/fV/2qfVu2ZrflTk-TnRQEDdDw/A-Better-Way-to-Go-vUSPIRG.pdf |accessdate=April 23, 2008}}</ref> The city's extraordinary public transit use means that New Yorkers emit far fewer greenhouse gases on a per capita basis than the average American. New York City's greenhouse gas emissions are 7.1 metric tons per person compared with the national average of 24.5.<ref name=\"NYC emissions\"/> New Yorkers are collectively responsible for one percent of the nation's total [[greenhouse gas]] emissions<ref name=\"NYC emissions\"/> though comprising 2.7% of the nation's population.\n\n===Green building===\n<!-- Image with inadequate rationale removed: [[File:Ecotower.jpg|thumb|230px|The [[Bank of America Tower, New York City|Bank of America Tower]] is the first skyscraper ever to attain Platinum [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] certification.]] -->\nFor years New York City was slow to embrace [[green building]] guidelines used in cities like San Francisco to promote [[environmentally friendly]] construction. In the post-World War II construction boom, changes in zoning regulations and the widespread use of air conditioning led to the design of sealed glass and steel towers. Without natural sources of light and ventilation, such buildings required large amounts of fossil fuels to operate.\n\nThis phase of building style is rapidly changing in New York, which has become a leader in energy-efficient green office buildings like [[7 World Trade Center]], which recycles rainwater and uses it in toilets and for irrigation, and computer-controlled heating and lighting. The United States Green Building Council estimates 3,000 new green apartments in New York City have been built since 2001.\n\nIn 2000 the state of New York introduced a green building tax credit, the first one of its kind in the United States, that has allowed some developers of environmentally friendly buildings to write off as much as $6 million on their tax bill. The city's Department of Design and Construction developed a set of guidelines in 1999 that encourage environmentally sound building methods for municipal projects. The guidelines had led to approximately $700 million in green city construction projects by the end of 2005.<ref>[http://www.gothamgazette.com/article/issueoftheweek/20040105/200/817 \"Green Buildings.\" ''Gotham Gazette'' 5 January 2004]</ref> In 2005, New York City mandated that nonresidential public buildings costing $2 million or more be built to standards set by [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design]] (LEED), which grade buildings in areas like energy and water consumption, [[indoor air quality]] and use of renewable materials. The legislation also applies to private projects that receive $10 million or more in public funds or half of whose budgets come from public money.\n\n==Air pollution==\nPrior to the passage of the federal [[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act of 1970]] and other local and state regulations in the late 60s, New York City suffered severe [[smog]], with several instances of major smog events like the [[1966 New York City smog]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/29/nyregion/you-should-have-seen-air-53-after-sept-11-considering-history-s-lessons.html |first=Kirk |last=Johnson |title=You Should Have Seen the Air in '53; After Sept. 11, Considering History's Lessons on Pollution |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 29, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527215547/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/29/nyregion/you-should-have-seen-air-53-after-sept-11-considering-history-s-lessons.html |archivedate=May 27, 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n===High cancer risk from airborne chemicals===\n\nAccording to the most recent [[Environmental Protection Agency]] National-Scale Air Toxics Assessment study,<ref>{{cite web |title=US Environmental Protection Agency |url=http://www.epa.gov/nata2002/tables.html |work=National-Scale Air Toxics Assessment 2002 County-Level Modeled Ambient Concentrations, Exposures, and Risks |accessdate=August 27, 2011 |year=2002 |quote=The risk estimates are limited to consideration of inhalation exposure. People receive substantial additional exposures to air pollutants such as mercury and PCBs that bioaccumulate in food. In addition, this assessment does not include emissions from indoor sources of air toxics. Studies have shown that many people receive substantial additional inhalation exposure to common indoor air pollutants such as formaldehyde and perchloroethylene. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111112012/http://www.epa.gov/nata2002/tables.html |archivedate=January 11, 2012 }}</ref> residents of [[Manhattan|New York County]], NY (Manhattan), have the third highest cancer risk caused by airborne chemicals of all [[County (United States)|counties]] in the United States (including the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the Virgin Islands), following only [[Tippah County, Mississippi]] (highest risk), and [[Boyd County, Kentucky]] (second highest risk). [[The Bronx|Bronx]] and [[Brooklyn|Kings]] Counties rank 8th and 9th out of the 3,223 counties and county-equivalents in the United States, while [[Queens]] County ranks 13th nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=2002 NATA US Cancer Risks County |url=http://www.epa.gov/ttn/atw/nata2002/countyxls/cancer_risk02_county_042009.xls}}</ref>\n\n\n\nThe 2009 annual report of the [[American Lung Association]] ranks the New York City region as 22nd among the top 25 regions in the United States most affected by year-round particle pollution, and 17th of the top 25 most polluted cities.\n\n===Emissions management===\n\nNew York has the largest hybrid bus fleet in the country, and some of the first hybrid taxis. A large percentage of the city-owned vehicle fleet, including the personal cars of top city officials, are required since 2005 to be fuel efficient hybrid vehicles like the [[Toyota Prius]] or [[Honda Accord]] gas-electric sedan that produce minimal particulates and carbon dioxide emissions. In 2005 the city's vehicle fleet had 6,000 alternative fuel and 70 electric vehicles. A [[biodiesel]] processing plant will soon open in Brooklyn that will process {{convert|2.5|e6USgal|m3}} of biodiesel a year and distribute it to conventional gas stations in the city.<ref name=\"ny.metro.us\"/>\n\nThe [[New York City Department of Sanitation|Department of Sanitation]], which has 1,500 trucks of its 2,200-vehicle fleet on the streets each day, is working with truck manufacturers to introduce gas-electric hybrid garbage trucks. The Department switched to using low-sulfur fuel in 2001 and uses corn-based ethanol in 500 of its 1,500 light-duty trucks.<ref>\"Eco-rig a Sanitation Sensation.\" ''The New York Post'' April 3, 2006.</ref>\n\n[[File:Hybrid taxis NYC 07 2010 9752.JPG|thumb|[[New York City]] has more than 2,000 [[hybrid taxi]]s as of mid 2009, more than any other city in North America<ref name=GreenCG1>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2009/10/fords-us-hybrid-sales-up-73-for-first-9-months-of-2009-total-us-hybrid-sales-down-14-for-same-period.html |title=Ford's US Hybrid Sales Up 73% for First 9 Months of 2009; Total US Hybrid Sales Down 14% for Same Period |publisher=[[Green Car Congress]] |date=October 14, 2009 |accessdate=October 17, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infotaxi.org/article_142.htm |title=Hybrid taxis slowly catching on in the west |publisher=Infotaxi |author=Fred Gober |accessdate=October 17, 2009}}</ref> (although it is also the largest city in North America).]]\n\nAir pollution is an ongoing political issue in neighborhoods that contain bus depots.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n==Water supply==\n{{main article|New York City water supply system}}\nMany of the city's environmental assets are related to geography and a long tradition of environmental stewardship in the mountain ranges north of the city. Because the watershed is in one of the largest protected wilderness areas in the United States, the natural water filtration process remains intact. As a result, New York is one of only five major cities in the United States with drinking water pure enough to require only chlorination to ensure its purity at the tap under normal conditions.<ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/news/tokyo2.html \"Maintaining Water Quality that Satisfies Customers: New York City Watershed Agricultural Program\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061012182905/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/news/tokyo2.html |date=October 12, 2006 }}, ''New York City Department of Environmental Protection'', November 20, 1998.</ref><ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/drinking_water/wsstate.shtml \"2010 Drinking Water Supply and Quality Report\"], \"City of New York Department of Environmental Protection\" 2011.</ref>\n\nHowever, all groundwater entering New York City's distribution system is treated with [[chlorine]], [[fluoride]], food-grade phosphoric acid, and, in some cases, [[sodium hydroxide]]. New York City uses chlorine to meet the New York State Sanitary Code and federal Safe Drinking Water Act disinfection requirements. Fluoride, at a concentration of one part per million, is added to help prevent tooth decay and has been added since 1966 in accordance with the New York City Health Code. Phosphoric acid is added to create a protective film on pipes that reduces the release of metals such as lead and copper from household plumbing. Additionally, a sequestering phosphate is applied at several wells to prevent the precipitation of naturally occurring minerals, mostly iron and manganese, in the distribution mains and customers' household piping. Air stripper facilities can be operated at several wells to remove volatile organic compounds (VOCs). The only well in operation in 2007 had an air stripper in operation.<ref>[http://nyc.gov/html/dep/html/drinking_water/groundwater.shtml#treatment New York City Groundwater System for 2007 - Treatment]</ref>\n\n[[File:Ashokan Reservoir.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Ashokan Reservoir]] is one of several providing drinking water for New York City.]]\n\nThe complex [[New York City water supply system]]&mdash;with 19 reservoirs bringing mountain water from as far as {{convert|125|mi|km}} away through a gravity-fed web of aqueducts &mdash; consists of three different systems. The [[New Croton Reservoir|Croton]] system, the oldest and smallest section, sits in [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] and [[Putnam County, New York|Putnam]] Counties. The second oldest is the Catskill system. In the early years of the 20th century, the city and state designated thousands of acres the eastern Catskills to build two reservoirs that more than doubled the city's capacity. In the 1950s and 1960s, the city expanded again, tapping the east and west branches of the [[Delaware River]] and other tributaries to create the newest and largest of its three systems.\n\nThe Croton system is the source of some [[turbidity]] issues for the city's water. The turbidity problem stems largely from conditions that have been present in the Catskill system from the beginning. Engineering studies in 1903 recognized that the clay of the steeply sloped Eastern Catskills turned the clear waters of the Schoharie and Esopus Creeks muddy after storms.\n\nEngineers decided to go ahead anyway, devising a two-reservoir system with built-in turbidity controls. The city has sought to restrict development throughout its watershed.  One of its largest watershed protection programs is the Land Acquisition Program, under which the New York City Department of Environmental Protection has purchased or protected through conservation easement over 70,000 acres (280&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) since 1997.<ref>\"New York\u2019s Water Supply May Need Filtering.\" July 20, 2006 ''The New York Times'' [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/20/nyregion/20water.html?hp&ex=1153454400&en=2be183debc88eae7&ei=5094&partner=homepage]</ref>\n\nIn the 12 months that ended on June 30, 2006, daily consumption averaged {{convert|1.086|e9USgal|m3}} in the city, a decline of 5.2% since 2002 and the lowest total daily use since 1951, when the city had about 7.9 million people and New York was experiencing a severe drought. Daily consumption peaked at {{convert|1.512|e9USgal|m3}} in 1979; in the next year\u2019s census, the city\u2019s population was 7.1 million, its lowest since 1930. Despite having grown to a population of 8.2 million in 2006, the city is now using 28% less water than it did in 1979. The drop in consumption is mostly a result of city policy; water-saving plumbing fixtures and devices in renovations and new construction are required, the city has been more diligent in finding and fixing leaks, and since the late 1980s it has been metering residential customers\u2019 water use. The city uses sonar and other equipment to more efficiently find and fix leaks in its millions of feet of water mains and has taken steps like installing sprinkler caps on fire hydrants during the summer, letting overheated kids cool off without torrents of gushing water.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/03/nyregion/03water.html \"More Masses Huddling, but They Use Less Water\"], ''New York Times'', October 3, 2006.</ref>\n\n==Garbage disposal==\nIn September 2012, ''[[Travel+Leisure]]'' named New York City the #1 \"America's Dirtiest City\", from the results of a readership survey rating 35 \"Favorite Cities\" in the United States.\n\nIn 2001 Mayor [[Rudolph Giuliani]] closed the [[Fresh Kills Landfill]] on [[Staten Island]]. The City did not have a subsequent plan for garbage disposal. An interim system was put in place in which most of the city's garbage was trucked out of the city to land fills in other states. This generated an unacceptable amount of truck traffic in low-income neighborhoods, leading to exacerbated air pollution.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} In 2006 Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] signed legislation establishing a new solid waste management plan, which will use barges and trains to export 90% of the city\u2019s 12,000 daily tons of residential trash. Under the previous scheme trucks and tractor-trailers were used for 84% of the trash. Passage of the new legislation was delayed by opponents in a Manhattan neighborhood who protested the use of a marine transfer station in the [[Hudson River Park]]. Environmentalists and social activists argued the plan promoted [[environmental justice]] because no one borough or neighborhood would bear a disproportionate burden under the proposal, and they therefore supported it.\n\n==Other issues==\nMuch of the city's housing stock is old, and lead paint is an ongoing public health issue. Some parts of the city are also at risk if current global warming patterns continue and sea levels rise.\n\nThe city is home to several thriving non-native species of plants and animals. Populations of wild South American [[monk parakeet]]s, also known as the Quaker parrot, live in Greenwood Cemetery, Marine Park, Bensonhurst, and Bay Ridge in Brooklyn, and in the East Bronx.\n\nA 2014 paper estimated the [[rats in New York City|rat population of New York City]] proper to be about 2 million, or one for every four people.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Does New York City really have as many rats as people? |author=Jonathan Auerbach |date=October 3, 2014 |journal=Significance |volume=11 |issue=4 |doi=10.1111/j.1740-9713.2014.00764.x |pages=22\u201327}}</ref>\n\n===Farmers' markets===\n{{main article|Food and water in New York City#Greenmarket}}\n[[File:Union Square Farmers Market.jpg|thumb|The [[farmers' market]] at [[Union Square (New York City)|Union Square]].]]\nIn 1976 the Council on the Environment of New York City established the Greenmarket program, which provides regional small family farmers opportunities to sell their fruits, vegetables and other farm products at open-air markets in city public squares. The Greenmarket program manages 45 markets in the five boroughs. More than 100 New York City restaurants source their ingredients from Greenmarket farmers each week; Greenmarket farmers also annually donate about 500,000 pounds of food to City Harvest and other hunger relief organizations each year. The most famous location is the Union Square Greenmarket, held Monday, Wednesday, Friday, and Saturday between 8 a.m. and 6 p.m. year-round. The market has 250,000 customers a week who purchase 1,000 varieties of fruits and vegetables at the market.\n\nThe markets are anchored by 164 farmers who travel a median distance of {{convert|90|mi|km}}, including 90 vegetable and orchard growers, 29 meat, dairy, poultry, wool and fish producers, 12 producers of honey, [[maple syrup]], jam, and wine, 19 growers of plants and flowers, and 14 bakers.\n\nIn 2006 the City Council announced it would make [[farmers' market]]s the centerpiece of efforts to reduce hunger and increase awareness of nutrition in the city, especially in lower-income areas, and that 10 new farmers' markets would open serving low-income neighborhoods including [[public housing]] projects.\n\n===Greenpoint oil spill===\n{{main article|Greenpoint oil spill}}\nThe [[Greenpoint, Brooklyn|Greenpoint]] neighborhood of Brooklyn was once home to many [[oil refineries]] for more than a century. In 1950, the predecessor of the [[ExxonMobil]] oil company was alleged to have spilled {{convert|17|e6USgal|m3}} of oil into [[Newtown Creek]] in what is one of the worst oil spills in United States history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nymag.com/news/features/32865/ |title=The Ooze |accessdate=April 19, 2015 |publisher=New York Magazine}}</ref> Oil continues seeping into a city waterway decades after the leak was first noticed.\n\nThe oil business has largely moved elsewhere, but countless small and large spills went unnoticed for decades and eventually formed a subterranean blob of more than {{convert|50|acre|m2}}. Authorities have been aware of the problem since 1978. [[Exxon Mobil]] accepted responsibility for much of the damage in 1990 and has since pumped some {{convert|9|e6USgal|m3}} out of the ground.\n\nThe slow pace of the cleanup, however, has increasingly angered Greenpoint residents and elected officials, who have launched a series of lawsuits against Exxon in 2004. In June 2006 the [[New York State Department of Environmental Conservation]] announced it would sue Exxon Mobil to hasten completion of the cleanup.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Climate change in New York City]]\n*[[Health effects arising from the September 11 attacks]]\n*[[OneNYC]]\n*[[PlaNYC]]\n*[[New York City Department of Environmental Protection]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nyc.gov/html/oec/html/home/home.shtml New York City Office of Environmental Coordination]\n*[https://aerostate.io/blog/Air-quality-in-New-York-and-Manhattan.html Air quality in New York and Manhattan]\n\n{{New York City}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Environmental Issues In New York City}}\n[[Category:Environmental issues in New York City|New York]]\n[[Category:Recycling in New York City]]\n[[Category:Environmental justice in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n[[File:Jacqueline_Kennedy_Onassis_Reservoir.jpg|275px|thumb|alt=Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis Reservoir in Central Park|[[Central Park]]'s reservoirs were historically important components of the [[New York City water supply system]].]]\n'''Environmental issues in [[New York City]]''' are  affected by the city's size, density, [[Transportation in New York City|abundant public transportation infrastructure]], and location at the mouth of the [[Hudson River]].\n\nNew York's population density has environmental pros and cons. It facilitates the highest [[mass transit]] use in the United States, but also concentrates pollution. [[Gasoline consumption]] in the city is at the rate the national average was in the 1920s,<ref name=\"New York City energy consumption\" /> and [[greenhouse gas]] emissions are a fraction of the national average, at 7.1 metric tons per person per year, below San Francisco, at 11.2 metric tons, and the national average, at 24.5 metric tons.<ref name=\"NYC emissions\">{{cite news |title=Inventory of New York City Greenhouse Gas Emissions |author=New York City Office of Long-term Planning and Sustainability |date=April 2007 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/om/pdf/ccp_report041007.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=April 11, 2007}}</ref> New York City accounts for only 1% of United States greenhouse gas emissions while housing 2.7% of its population.<ref name=\"NYC emissions\"/>\nIn September 2012, New York was named the #1 \"America's Dirtiest City,\" by a ''[[Travel+Leisure]]'' readership survey that rated the environmental quality of 35 prominent cities in the United States.\n\n==Population density in New York City==\n\nEnvironmental concerns in the city involve managing the city's extraordinary [[population density]].  Mass transit use is the highest in the nation and gasoline consumption in the city is at the rate the national average was in the 1920s.<ref name=\"New York City energy consumption\">{{cite book |first=Ben |last=Jervey |title=The Big Green Apple: Your Guide to Eco-Friendly Living in New York City |isbn=978-0-7627-3835-9 |publisher=Globe Pequot Press |year=2006 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/biggreenappleyou00jerv }}</ref> New York City's dense population and low [[automobile dependence]] help make New York among the most [[energy efficiency in transportation|energy efficient]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |author=Owen, David |title=Green Manhattan |publisher=The New Yorker |date=October 18, 2004}}</ref> The city's greenhouse gas emission levels are relatively low when measured per capita, at 7.1 metric tons per person, below [[San Francisco]], at 11.2 metric tons, and the national average, at 24.5.<ref name=\"NYC emissions\"/>  New Yorkers are collectively responsible for one percent of the nation's total [[greenhouse gas]] emissions,<ref name=\"NYC emissions\"/> though comprise 2.7% of the nation's population.  The average New Yorker consumes less than half the electricity used by a resident of San Francisco and nearly one-quarter the electricity consumed by a resident of [[Dallas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/planyc2030/html/challenge/faq.shtml |title=Global Warming and Greenhouse Gases |publisher=[[PlaNYC]] / The City of New York |date=December 6, 2006 |accessdate=December 13, 2006}}</ref>\n\nConcentrated pollution in New York City leads to high incidence of [[asthma]] and other respiratory conditions among the city's residents.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Urban Asthma and the Neighbourhood Environment  New York City |author1=Coburn, Jason |author2=Jeffrey Osleeb |author3=Michael Porter |journal=Health & Place |date=June 2006 |volume=12 |pages=167\u2013179 |pmid=16338632 |doi=10.1016/j.healthplace.2004.11.002 |issue=2}}</ref>  In recent years the city has focused on reducing its environmental impact. The city government is required to purchase only the most energy-efficient equipment for use in city offices and public housing.<ref>{{cite news |author=DePalma, Anthony |title=It Never Sleeps, but It's Learned to Douse the Lights |publisher=The New York Times |date=December 11, 2005 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/11/nyregion/11efficiency.html |accessdate=July 19, 2006}}</ref> New York has the largest clean air diesel-[[hybrid vehicle|hybrid]] and [[compressed natural gas]] bus fleet in the country, and some of the first hybrid taxis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/nyct/bus/centennial/page2.htm |title=A Century of Buses in New York City |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority |accessdate=November 17, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060525043420/http://mta.info/nyct/bus/centennial/page2.htm |archivedate=July 14, 2016 |url-status=dead }}\n* See also {{cite press release |url=http://www.sierraclub.org/pressroom/releases/pr2005-07-01a.asp |title=New York City\u2019s Yellow Cabs Go Green |publisher=Sierra Club |date=July 1, 2005 |accessdate=July 19, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107223735/http://www.sierraclub.org/pressroom/releases/pr2005-07-01a.asp |archivedate=January 7, 2009 }}</ref> The city is also a leader in the construction of energy-efficient [[green building|green office buildings]], including the [[Hearst Tower (New York City)|Hearst Tower]] among others.<ref name=\"greenbuilding\">{{cite news |title=7 World Trade Center and Hearst Building: New York's Test Cases for Environmentally Aware Office Towers |publisher=The New York Times |date=April 16, 2006 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/16/arts/design/16gree.html |accessdate=July 19, 2006 |author=Pogrebin, Robin |authorlink=Robin Pogrebin}}</ref>\n\nNew York City is supplied with drinking water by the protected [[Catskill Mountains]] [[Drainage basin|watershed]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/maplevels.html |title=Although New york tap water is safe to drink the water quality is not all that impressive and although the city has made efforts to improve the water quality they will never achieve standards set by those cities in asia such as Singapore and hong kong Current Reservoir Levels |publisher=New York City Department of Environmental Protection |accessdate=June 4, 2007}}</ref> As a result of the watershed's integrity and undisturbed natural water filtration process, New York is one of only five major cities in the United States with drinking water pure enough not to require purification by [[water treatment]] plants.<ref>{{cite conference|last=Miele |first=Joel A., Sr |title=Maintaining Water Quality that Satisfies Customers: New York City Watershed Agricultural Program |booktitle=International Water Supply Symposium Tokyo 1998 |publisher=New York City Department of Environmental Protection |date=November 20, 1998 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/news/tokyo2.html |accessdate=November 17, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061012182905/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/news/tokyo2.html |archivedate=October 12, 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New York City 2005 Drinking Water Supply and Quality Report |publisher=New York City Department of Environmental Protection |year=2005 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/pdf/wsstat05.pdf |accessdate=July 17, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Policy and influence==\n[[File:Castelloplan.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Lower Manhattan in 1660, when it was part of [[New Amsterdam]] (Nieuw Amsterdam).]]\n\n{{details|Large Cities Climate Leadership Group}}\n\n{{as of|2005}}, the city has focused on reducing its environmental impact. The city government is required to purchase only the most energy-efficient equipment for use in city offices and public housing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/11/nyregion/11efficiency.html |title=It Never Sleeps, but It's Learned to Douse the Lights |publisher=New York Times |date=December 11, 2005 |accessdate=July 19, 2006 |first=Anthony |last=Depalma}}</ref> New York has the largest clean-air diesel-[[hybrid vehicle|hybrid]] and [[compressed natural gas]] bus fleet in the country, and some of the first hybrid taxis.<ref>\n* Metropolitan Transportation Authority [http://web.mta.info/nyct/bus/centennial/page2.htm Different Buses for Different Jobs] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060525043420/http://mta.info/nyct/bus/centennial/page2.htm |date=May 25, 2006 }}, retrieved on July 14, 2016\n* {{cite news |title=New York City\u2019s Yellow Cabs Go Green |publisher=Sierra Club press release |date=July 1, 2005 |url=http://www.sierraclub.org/pressroom/releases/pr2005-07-01a.asp |accessdate=July 19, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107223735/http://www.sierraclub.org/pressroom/releases/pr2005-07-01a.asp |archivedate=January 7, 2009 }}</ref> The city is also a leader in energy-efficient \"green\" office buildings, such as [[Hearst Tower (New York City)|Hearst Tower]] and [[7 World Trade Center]].<ref name=\"greenbuilding\"/>\n\nEnvironmental groups make large efforts to help shape legislation in New York because they see the strategy as an efficient way to influence national programs. New York City's economy is larger than Switzerland's, a size that means the city has potential to set new ''de facto'' standards. Manufacturers are also attuned to the latest trends and needs in the city because the market is simply too big to ignore.\n\nEx-mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] is one of 248 mayors from 41 states to have signed the U.S. Mayors Climate Protection Agreement. Under the agreement, mayors \"strive to meet or beat the Kyoto Protocol targets in their own communities\". The city was a petitioner in the landmark ''[[Massachusetts v. Environmental Protection Agency]]'' Supreme Court case forcing the EPA to regulate [[greenhouse gases]] as pollutants.\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Energy efficiency==\n{{Bar chart\n| title       = Average annual residential electricity usage by city, 2000-2005<ref>{{cite news |title=New York City's Climate Change Challenges through 2030 |author=New York City Mayor's Office of Sustainability |year=2007 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/planyc2030/downloads/pdf/greenyc_climate-change.pdf |accessdate=February 28, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712134102/http://www.nyc.gov/html/planyc2030/downloads/pdf/greenyc_climate-change.pdf |archive-date=July 12, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| label_type  = City\n| data_type   = per-customer kwh use\n| bar_width   = 300\n| width_units = px\n| data_max    = 17000\n| float       = right\n| label1   = {{hilite|New York City}}\n| data1    = 4696\n| label2   = San Francisco\n| data2    = 6753\n| label3   = Chicago\n| data3    = 8143\n| label4   = Phoenix\n| data4    = 13344\n| label5   = Houston\n| data5    = 14542\n| label6   = Dallas\n| data6    = 16611\n}}\n\nThe city's unique density, encouraged by much of it being surrounded by water, facilitates the highest rate of mass transit use in the United States. New York is one of the most [[Efficient energy use|energy efficient]] cities in the United States as a result. Gasoline consumption in New York is at the rate the national average was in the 1920s.<ref name=\"ny.metro.us\">Jervey, Ben, [http://ny.metro.us/metro/local/article/A_guide_for_perplexed_wouldbe_ecofriends/730.html \"The Big Green Apple: Your Guide to Eco-Friendly Living in New York City\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060626061239/http://ny.metro.us/metro/local/article/A_guide_for_perplexed_wouldbe_ecofriends/730.html |date=June 26, 2006 }}, ''Metro New York''.</ref>  The city's mass transit system, multifamily housing, mixed neighborhoods and the fact that [[greenfield land]] is no longer available to development, make building in New York very energy efficient. New York City has a larger population than all but eleven states, and consumes less energy per-capita than any.<ref>Owen, David, [http://www.greenbelt.org/downloads/resources/newswire_11_04GreenManhattan.pdf \"Green Manhattan]\", ''The New Yorker'', October 18, 2004</ref> The average New Yorker consumes a little more than half of the electricity of someone who lives in Chicago and nearly one-quarter the electricity consumed by someone who lives in Dallas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Warming and Greenhouse Gases |publisher=[[PlaNYC]] |date=December 6, 2006 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/planyc2030/html/about/faq.shtml#warming-6 |accessdate=December 13, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070109085743/http://www.nyc.gov/html/planyc2030/html/about/faq.shtml |archivedate=January 9, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, New York faces growing energy demands and limited space. The city has introduced a series of environmental policies since the 1990s to address these problems. Detailed measures included switching more than 11,000 traffic lights and pedestrian signals in the city to new energy-efficient [[light-emitting diodes]] that use 90% less energy than conventional fixtures. The city replaced 149,000 \"cobra head\" street lights with new energy-efficient designs by 2008. Over 180,000 inefficient refrigerators in public [[New York City Housing Authority|housing projects]] have been replaced with new ones that use a quarter of the power of the old ones. By law, the city government can purchase only the most efficient cars, air-conditioners and copy machines.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/11/nyregion/11efficiency.html \"It Never Sleeps, but It's Learned to Douse the Lights\"], ''The New York Times'', December 11, 2005.</ref>  The electricity used to power the [[Statue of Liberty]], [[Ellis Island]] and 22 other federal buildings in New York City, an annual electricity demand of roughly 27 million kilowatt hours, is provided by wind power.<ref>[http://www.gothamgazette.com/article/environment/20060308/7/1782 \"Wind Power In NYC\"], ''Gotham Gazette'', March 8, 2006.</ref>\n\nNew York City is home to several clean energy projects. Two attempts to provide electricity to [[Roosevelt Island]] by installing underwater turbines in the [[East River]] failed when the turbine blades were torn off by currents. An improved turbine design proved to be successful and on January 23, 2012 [[FERC]] issued a 10-year pilot commercial license to Verdant Power\u2019s RITE Project \u2013 the first commercial license for tidal power in the United States. Under the license, Verdant Power expects to generate up to 1 megawatt after a staged installation of up to 30 turbines. Planning is also underway to construct windmills on a hill in the former [[Fresh Kills Landfill]]. The wind energy project would power 5,000 homes on Staten Island.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\n\n===Transportation===\n\n{{main article|Transportation in New York City}}\n\nNew York is distinguished from other American cities by its extensive use of [[public transportation]]. While nearly 90% of Americans drive to their jobs, public transit is overwhelmingly dominant for New Yorkers.<ref name=\"bts.gov\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bts.gov/publications/highlights_of_the_2001_national_household_travel_survey/html/executive_summary.html |title=Bureau of Transportation Statistics, U.S. Department of Transportation |access-date=August 27, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002070118/http://www.bts.gov/publications/highlights_of_the_2001_national_household_travel_survey/html/executive_summary.html |archive-date=October 2, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> According to the [[United States 2000 Census|2000 U.S. Census]], New York City is the only locality in the United States where more than half of all households do not own a car (the figure is even higher in Manhattan, over 75%; nationally, the rate is 8%).<ref name=\"bts.gov\"/> About one-third of users of mass transit in the United States and two-thirds of the nation's rail riders live in New York and its suburbs, and New York City's public transit system accounts for nearly four times as many passenger miles as the [[Washington, D.C. Metropolitan Area|Washington, D.C.]], and [[Los Angeles metropolitan area|Los Angeles]] metro regions combined.<ref>The Metropolitan Transportation Authority. [http://web.mta.info/mta/network.htm Network]; and David Owens.</ref> Only 6% of shopping trips by New Yorkers involve the use of a car.<ref>[http://www.transalt.org/press/releases/060223necessity_choice.html \"Necessity or Choice? Why People Drive in Manhattan.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060908144835/http://www.transalt.org/press/releases/060223necessity_choice.html |date=September 8, 2006 }} ''[[Transportation Alternatives]]'' Feb 2006.</ref>\n\nNew York City's high rate of transit use saved {{convert|1.8|e9USgal|m3}} of oil in 2006 and $4.6 billion in gasoline costs. New York saves half of all the oil saved by transit nationwide. The reduction in oil consumption meant 11.8 million metric tons of carbon dioxide pollution was kept out of the air.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Better Way to Go: Meeting America's 21st Century Transportation Challenges with Modern Public Transit |publisher=U.S. Public Interest Research Group |date=March 2008 |url=http://www.uspirg.org/uploads/2q/fV/2qfVu2ZrflTk-TnRQEDdDw/A-Better-Way-to-Go-vUSPIRG.pdf |accessdate=April 23, 2008}}</ref> The city's extraordinary public transit use means that New Yorkers emit far fewer greenhouse gases on a per capita basis than the average American. New York City's greenhouse gas emissions are 7.1 metric tons per person compared with the national average of 24.5.<ref name=\"NYC emissions\"/> New Yorkers are collectively responsible for one percent of the nation's total [[greenhouse gas]] emissions<ref name=\"NYC emissions\"/> though comprising 2.7% of the nation's population.\n\n===Green building===\n<!-- Image with inadequate rationale removed: [[File:Ecotower.jpg|thumb|230px|The [[Bank of America Tower, New York City|Bank of America Tower]] is the first skyscraper ever to attain Platinum [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] certification.]] -->\nFor years New York City was slow to embrace [[green building]] guidelines used in cities like San Francisco to promote [[environmentally friendly]] construction. In the post-World War II construction boom, changes in zoning regulations and the widespread use of air conditioning led to the design of sealed glass and steel towers. Without natural sources of light and ventilation, such buildings required large amounts of fossil fuels to operate.\n\nThis phase of building style is rapidly changing in New York, which has become a leader in energy-efficient green office buildings like [[7 World Trade Center]], which recycles rainwater and uses it in toilets and for irrigation, and computer-controlled heating and lighting. The United States Green Building Council estimates 3,000 new green apartments in New York City have been built since 2001.\n\nIn 2000 the state of New York introduced a green building tax credit, the first one of its kind in the United States, that has allowed some developers of environmentally friendly buildings to write off as much as $6 million on their tax bill. The city's Department of Design and Construction developed a set of guidelines in 1999 that encourage environmentally sound building methods for municipal projects. The guidelines had led to approximately $700 million in green city construction projects by the end of 2005.<ref>[http://www.gothamgazette.com/article/issueoftheweek/20040105/200/817 \"Green Buildings.\" ''Gotham Gazette'' 5 January 2004]</ref> In 2005, New York City mandated that nonresidential public buildings costing $2 million or more be built to standards set by [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design]] (LEED), which grade buildings in areas like energy and water consumption, [[indoor air quality]] and use of renewable materials. The legislation also applies to private projects that receive $10 million or more in public funds or half of whose budgets come from public money.\n\n==Air pollution==\nPrior to the passage of the federal [[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act of 1970]] and other local and state regulations in the late 60s, New York City suffered severe [[smog]], with several instances of major smog events like the [[1966 New York City smog]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/29/nyregion/you-should-have-seen-air-53-after-sept-11-considering-history-s-lessons.html |first=Kirk |last=Johnson |title=You Should Have Seen the Air in '53; After Sept. 11, Considering History's Lessons on Pollution |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 29, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527215547/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/29/nyregion/you-should-have-seen-air-53-after-sept-11-considering-history-s-lessons.html |archivedate=May 27, 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n===High cancer risk from airborne chemicals===\n\nAccording to the most recent [[Environmental Protection Agency]] National-Scale Air Toxics Assessment study,<ref>{{cite web |title=US Environmental Protection Agency |url=http://www.epa.gov/nata2002/tables.html |work=National-Scale Air Toxics Assessment 2002 County-Level Modeled Ambient Concentrations, Exposures, and Risks |accessdate=August 27, 2011 |year=2002 |quote=The risk estimates are limited to consideration of inhalation exposure. People receive substantial additional exposures to air pollutants such as mercury and PCBs that bioaccumulate in food. In addition, this assessment does not include emissions from indoor sources of air toxics. Studies have shown that many people receive substantial additional inhalation exposure to common indoor air pollutants such as formaldehyde and perchloroethylene. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111112012/http://www.epa.gov/nata2002/tables.html |archivedate=January 11, 2012 }}</ref> residents of [[Manhattan|New York County]], NY (Manhattan), have the third highest cancer risk caused by airborne chemicals of all [[County (United States)|counties]] in the United States (including the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the Virgin Islands), following only [[Tippah County, Mississippi]] (highest risk), and [[Boyd County, Kentucky]] (second highest risk). [[The Bronx|Bronx]] and [[Brooklyn|Kings]] Counties rank 8th and 9th out of the 3,223 counties and county-equivalents in the United States, while [[Queens]] County ranks 13th nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=2002 NATA US Cancer Risks County |url=http://www.epa.gov/ttn/atw/nata2002/countyxls/cancer_risk02_county_042009.xls}}</ref>\n\n\n\nThe 2009 annual report of the [[American Lung Association]] ranks the New York City region as 22nd among the top 25 regions in the United States most affected by year-round particle pollution, and 17th of the top 25 most polluted cities.\n\n===Emissions management===\n\nNew York has the largest hybrid bus fleet in the country, and some of the first hybrid taxis. A large percentage of the city-owned vehicle fleet, including the personal cars of top city officials, are required since 2005 to be fuel efficient hybrid vehicles like the [[Toyota Prius]] or [[Honda Accord]] gas-electric sedan that produce minimal particulates and carbon dioxide emissions. In 2005 the city's vehicle fleet had 6,000 alternative fuel and 70 electric vehicles. A [[biodiesel]] processing plant will soon open in Brooklyn that will process {{convert|2.5|e6USgal|m3}} of biodiesel a year and distribute it to conventional gas stations in the city.<ref name=\"ny.metro.us\"/>\n\nThe [[New York City Department of Sanitation|Department of Sanitation]], which has 1,500 trucks of its 2,200-vehicle fleet on the streets each day, is working with truck manufacturers to introduce gas-electric hybrid garbage trucks. The Department switched to using low-sulfur fuel in 2001 and uses corn-based ethanol in 500 of its 1,500 light-duty trucks.<ref>\"Eco-rig a Sanitation Sensation.\" ''The New York Post'' April 3, 2006.</ref>\n\n[[File:Hybrid taxis NYC 07 2010 9752.JPG|thumb|[[New York City]] has more than 2,000 [[hybrid taxi]]s as of mid 2009, more than any other city in North America<ref name=GreenCG1>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2009/10/fords-us-hybrid-sales-up-73-for-first-9-months-of-2009-total-us-hybrid-sales-down-14-for-same-period.html |title=Ford's US Hybrid Sales Up 73% for First 9 Months of 2009; Total US Hybrid Sales Down 14% for Same Period |publisher=[[Green Car Congress]] |date=October 14, 2009 |accessdate=October 17, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infotaxi.org/article_142.htm |title=Hybrid taxis slowly catching on in the west |publisher=Infotaxi |author=Fred Gober |accessdate=October 17, 2009}}</ref> (although it is also the largest city in North America).]]\n\nAir pollution is an ongoing political issue in neighborhoods that contain bus depots.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n==Water supply==\n{{main article|New York City water supply system}}\nMany of the city's environmental assets are related to geography and a long tradition of environmental stewardship in the mountain ranges north of the city. Because the watershed is in one of the largest protected wilderness areas in the United States, the natural water filtration process remains intact. As a result, New York is one of only five major cities in the United States with drinking water pure enough to require only chlorination to ensure its purity at the tap under normal conditions.<ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/news/tokyo2.html \"Maintaining Water Quality that Satisfies Customers: New York City Watershed Agricultural Program\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061012182905/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/news/tokyo2.html |date=October 12, 2006 }}, ''New York City Department of Environmental Protection'', November 20, 1998.</ref><ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/drinking_water/wsstate.shtml \"2010 Drinking Water Supply and Quality Report\"], \"City of New York Department of Environmental Protection\" 2011.</ref>\n\nHowever, all groundwater entering New York City's distribution system is treated with [[chlorine]], [[fluoride]], food-grade phosphoric acid, and, in some cases, [[sodium hydroxide]]. New York City uses chlorine to meet the New York State Sanitary Code and federal Safe Drinking Water Act disinfection requirements. Fluoride, at a concentration of one part per million, is added to help prevent tooth decay and has been added since 1966 in accordance with the New York City Health Code. Phosphoric acid is added to create a protective film on pipes that reduces the release of metals such as lead and copper from household plumbing. Additionally, a sequestering phosphate is applied at several wells to prevent the precipitation of naturally occurring minerals, mostly iron and manganese, in the distribution mains and customers' household piping. Air stripper facilities can be operated at several wells to remove volatile organic compounds (VOCs). The only well in operation in 2007 had an air stripper in operation.<ref>[http://nyc.gov/html/dep/html/drinking_water/groundwater.shtml#treatment New York City Groundwater System for 2007 - Treatment]</ref>\n\n[[File:Ashokan Reservoir.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Ashokan Reservoir]] is one of several providing drinking water for New York City.]]\n\nThe complex [[New York City water supply system]]&mdash;with 19 reservoirs bringing mountain water from as far as {{convert|125|mi|km}} away through a gravity-fed web of aqueducts &mdash; consists of three different systems. The [[New Croton Reservoir|Croton]] system, the oldest and smallest section, sits in [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] and [[Putnam County, New York|Putnam]] Counties. The second oldest is the Catskill system. In the early years of the 20th century, the city and state designated thousands of acres the eastern Catskills to build two reservoirs that more than doubled the city's capacity. In the 1950s and 1960s, the city expanded again, tapping the east and west branches of the [[Delaware River]] and other tributaries to create the newest and largest of its three systems.\n\nThe Croton system is the source of some [[turbidity]] issues for the city's water. The turbidity problem stems largely from conditions that have been present in the Catskill system from the beginning. Engineering studies in 1903 recognized that the clay of the steeply sloped Eastern Catskills turned the clear waters of the Schoharie and Esopus Creeks muddy after storms.\n\nEngineers decided to go ahead anyway, devising a two-reservoir system with built-in turbidity controls. The city has sought to restrict development throughout its watershed.  One of its largest watershed protection programs is the Land Acquisition Program, under which the New York City Department of Environmental Protection has purchased or protected through conservation easement over 70,000 acres (280&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) since 1997.<ref>\"New York\u2019s Water Supply May Need Filtering.\" July 20, 2006 ''The New York Times'' [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/20/nyregion/20water.html?hp&ex=1153454400&en=2be183debc88eae7&ei=5094&partner=homepage]</ref>\n\nIn the 12 months that ended on June 30, 2006, daily consumption averaged {{convert|1.086|e9USgal|m3}} in the city, a decline of 5.2% since 2002 and the lowest total daily use since 1951, when the city had about 7.9 million people and New York was experiencing a severe drought. Daily consumption peaked at {{convert|1.512|e9USgal|m3}} in 1979; in the next year\u2019s census, the city\u2019s population was 7.1 million, its lowest since 1930. Despite having grown to a population of 8.2 million in 2006, the city is now using 28% less water than it did in 1979. The drop in consumption is mostly a result of city policy; water-saving plumbing fixtures and devices in renovations and new construction are required, the city has been more diligent in finding and fixing leaks, and since the late 1980s it has been metering residential customers\u2019 water use. The city uses sonar and other equipment to more efficiently find and fix leaks in its millions of feet of water mains and has taken steps like installing sprinkler caps on fire hydrants during the summer, letting overheated kids cool off without torrents of gushing water.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/03/nyregion/03water.html \"More Masses Huddling, but They Use Less Water\"], ''New York Times'', October 3, 2006.</ref>\n\n==Garbage disposal==\nIn September 2012, ''[[Travel+Leisure]]'' named New York City the #1 \"America's Dirtiest City\", from the results of a readership survey rating 35 \"Favorite Cities\" in the United States.\n\nIn 2001 Mayor [[Rudolph Giuliani]] closed the [[Fresh Kills Landfill]] on [[Staten Island]]. The City did not have a subsequent plan for garbage disposal. An interim system was put in place in which most of the city's garbage was trucked out of the city to land fills in other states. This generated an unacceptable amount of truck traffic in low-income neighborhoods, leading to exacerbated air pollution.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} In 2006 Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] signed legislation establishing a new solid waste management plan, which will use barges and trains to export 90% of the city\u2019s 12,000 daily tons of residential trash. Under the previous scheme trucks and tractor-trailers were used for 84% of the trash. Passage of the new legislation was delayed by opponents in a Manhattan neighborhood who protested the use of a marine transfer station in the [[Hudson River Park]]. Environmentalists and social activists argued the plan promoted [[environmental justice]] because no one borough or neighborhood would bear a disproportionate burden under the proposal, and they therefore supported it.\n\n==Other issues==\nMuch of the city's housing stock is old, and lead paint is an ongoing public health issue. Some parts of the city are also at risk if current global warming patterns continue and sea levels rise.\n\nThe city is home to several thriving non-native species of plants and animals. Populations of wild South American [[monk parakeet]]s, also known as the Quaker parrot, live in Greenwood Cemetery, Marine Park, Bensonhurst, and Bay Ridge in Brooklyn, and in the East Bronx.\n\nA 2014 paper estimated the [[rats in New York City|rat population of New York City]] proper to be about 2 million, or one for every four people.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Does New York City really have as many rats as people? |author=Jonathan Auerbach |date=October 3, 2014 |journal=Significance |volume=11 |issue=4 |doi=10.1111/j.1740-9713.2014.00764.x |pages=22\u201327}}</ref>\n\n===Farmers' markets===\n{{main article|Food and water in New York City#Greenmarket}}\n[[File:Union Square Farmers Market.jpg|thumb|The [[farmers' market]] at [[Union Square (New York City)|Union Square]].]]\nIn 1976 the Council on the Environment of New York City established the Greenmarket program, which provides regional small family farmers opportunities to sell their fruits, vegetables and other farm products at open-air markets in city public squares. The Greenmarket program manages 45 markets in the five boroughs. More than 100 New York City restaurants source their ingredients from Greenmarket farmers each week; Greenmarket farmers also annually donate about 500,000 pounds of food to City Harvest and other hunger relief organizations each year. The most famous location is the Union Square Greenmarket, held Monday, Wednesday, Friday, and Saturday between 8 a.m. and 6 p.m. year-round. The market has 250,000 customers a week who purchase 1,000 varieties of fruits and vegetables at the market.\n\nThe markets are anchored by 164 farmers who travel a median distance of {{convert|90|mi|km}}, including 90 vegetable and orchard growers, 29 meat, dairy, poultry, wool and fish producers, 12 producers of honey, [[maple syrup]], jam, and wine, 19 growers of plants and flowers, and 14 bakers.\n\nIn 2006 the City Council announced it would make [[farmers' market]]s the centerpiece of efforts to reduce hunger and increase awareness of nutrition in the city, especially in lower-income areas, and that 10 new farmers' markets would open serving low-income neighborhoods including [[public housing]] projects.\n\n===Greenpoint oil spill===\n{{main article|Greenpoint oil spill}}\nThe [[Greenpoint, Brooklyn|Greenpoint]] neighborhood of Brooklyn was once home to many [[oil refineries]] for more than a century. In 1950, the predecessor of the [[ExxonMobil]] oil company was alleged to have spilled {{convert|17|e6USgal|m3}} of oil into [[Newtown Creek]] in what is one of the worst oil spills in United States history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nymag.com/news/features/32865/ |title=The Ooze |accessdate=April 19, 2015 |publisher=New York Magazine}}</ref> Oil continues seeping into a city waterway decades after the leak was first noticed.\n\nThe oil business has largely moved elsewhere, but countless small and large spills went unnoticed for decades and eventually formed a subterranean blob of more than {{convert|50|acre|m2}}. Authorities have been aware of the problem since 1978. [[Exxon Mobil]] accepted responsibility for much of the damage in 1990 and has since pumped some {{convert|9|e6USgal|m3}} out of the ground.\n\nThe slow pace of the cleanup, however, has increasingly angered Greenpoint residents and elected officials, who have launched a series of lawsuits against Exxon in 2004. In June 2006 the [[New York State Department of Environmental Conservation]] announced it would sue Exxon Mobil to hasten completion of the cleanup.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Climate change in New York City]]\n*[[Health effects arising from the September 11 attacks]]\n*[[OneNYC]]\n*[[PlaNYC]]\n*[[New York City Department of Environmental Protection]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nyc.gov/html/oec/html/home/home.shtml New York City Office of Environmental Coordination]\n*[https://aerostate.io/blog/Air-quality-in-New-York-and-Manhattan.html Air quality in New York and Manhattan]\n\n{{New York City}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Environmental Issues In New York City}}\n[[Category:Environmental issues in New York City|New York]]\n", "name_user": "Wil540 art", "label": "safe", "comment": "+Category:Recycling in New York City; +Category:Environmental justice in New York CityusingHotCat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environmental_issues_in_New_York_City"}
{"title_page": "Michael Flynn (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Mike Flynn (footballer)||text=English football player [[Mike Flynn (footballer)|Michael Anthony Flynn]]. For other people with the same name see [[Michael Flynn (disambiguation)]]}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Michael Flynn\n| image = MichaelFlynn.jpg\n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|10|17|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|6550|Mike Flynn|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Wales<ref name=Hugman/>\n| height = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]<ref name=Hugman/>\n| currentclub = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] (manager)\n| clubnumber = \n| years1 = 1999\u20132000\n| years2 = 2000\u20132001\n| years3 = 2000\u20132001\n| years4 = 2001\u20132002\n| years5 = 2002\u20132005\n| years6 = 2004\n| years7 = 2005\u20132007\n| years8 = 2007\u20132008\n| years9 = 2008\u20132009\n| years10 = 2008\n| years11 = 2009\u20132012\n| years12 = 2012\u20132015\n| years13 = 2015\u20132017\n| years14 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs1 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| clubs2 = [[Barry Town F.C.|Barry Town]]\n| clubs3 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| clubs4 = [[Barry Town F.C.|Barry Town]]\n| clubs5 = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] (loan)\n| clubs7 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n| clubs8 = [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]\n| clubs9 = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n| clubs10 = \u2192 [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] (loan)\n| clubs11 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n| clubs12 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| clubs13 = [[Undy Athletic A.F.C.|Undy Athletic]]\n| clubs14 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| caps1 = 20\n| goals1 = 4\n| caps2 = 8\n| goals2 = 12\n| caps3 = 3\n| goals3 = 1\n| caps4 = 12\n| goals4 = 12\n| caps5 = 37\n| goals5 = 2\n| caps6 = 6\n| goals6 = 0\n| caps7 = 97\n| goals7 = 19\n| caps8 = 26\n| goals8 = 3\n| caps9 = 25\n| goals9 = 4\n| caps10 = 4\n| goals10 = 0\n| caps11 = 91\n| goals11 = 10\n| caps12 = 82\n| goals12 = 5\n| caps13 = 4\n| goals13 = 3\n| caps14 = 5\n| goals14 = 0\n| totalcaps = 420\n| totalgoals = 75\n| manageryears1 = 2015\n| managerclubs1 = [[Undy Athletic A.F.C.|Undy Athletic]]\n| manageryears2 = 2017\n| managerclubs2 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] (caretaker)\n| manageryears3 = 2017\u2013\n| managerclubs3 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n}}\n'''Michael Flynn''' (born 17 October 1980) is a Welsh professional [[Manager (association football)|football manager]] and former [[Football player|player]] who played as a [[midfielder]]. He is the manager of {{English football updater|NewportC}} club [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]].\n\nFlynn began his career with Newport County, becoming a professional with [[Barry Town F.C.|Barry Town]] before his break out with [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]. He appeared 91 times for [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]. He returned to Newport County and played while obtaining his UEFA Pro License, however he became caretaker manager in 2017 amid a relegation battle.\n\nAfter 2017's 'Great Escape', Newport County won FA Cup fixtures against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]. In 2018 Newport also played [[The Premier League|Premier League]] team [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and in 2019 [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. In 2018\u201319 Flynn led Newport to the [[2019 EFL League Two play-off Final]] against [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Flynn started his career playing for [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] in 1999. A move to [[League of Wales]] club Barry Town beckoned in 2000. After forty goals in two seasons, including a goal in a 3\u20131 win over [[F.C. Porto]] in the second qualifying round of the Champions League, he moved to [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in the [[2002-03 in English football|2002\u201303 season]].\n\nFlynn spent a lot of his time on the substitutes' bench as Wigan won [[Football League Division Two|Division Two]] title. He made seventeen appearances in the league, fourteen of which came from the bench, and scored one goal. The next season did not start any better for Flynn as he started just one game and made seven appearances from the bench before he was loaned to then League One side [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]], where he started six times in the league and once in the [[FA Cup]] before returning to Wigan.\n\nIn the January [[transfer window]] of [[2004-05 in English football|that season]], Flynn joined [[Football League Championship|Championship]] strugglers Gillingham on a [[free transfer (football)|free transfer]]. Despite his instant success, and his three goals in sixteen starts, Gillingham were relegated to League One on the last day of the season.\n\nAlthough injury affected his [[2005-06 in English football|2005\u201306 season]], Flynn scored six goals. He took over as captain for the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307 season]] and became top scorer with twelve goals.\n\nIt was announced on 8 May 2007 that Flynn had been offered a new contract with Gillingham. He chose not to sign, and left the club when his contract expired at the end of June 2007.\n\nOn 5 July 2007, Flynn signed a one-year contract with [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]], with an option for a further year. On 3 December 2007, Flynn scored his first goal for Blackpool in the club's 1\u20131 away draw against [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]. On 7 May 2008 he was released by Blackpool.\nOn 23 July 2008, he became [[Stan Ternent]]'s fifth signing at League One side [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]. He, along with five other players, made his Town debut in the 1\u20131 draw against [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] at the [[Galpharm Stadium]] on 9 August 2008. On 27 August he scored his first goal for Huddersfield in the second round of the [[Football League Cup 2008-09|League Cup]] against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]. Town went on to lose the game 2\u20131. His first league goals for Town came in the 3\u20132 win over [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] at the [[Galpharm Stadium]] on 20 September 2008.\n\nFollowing a short spell on the sidelines following a [[hamstring]] injury, he joined [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] on loan on 27 November 2008. He made his debut in the 1\u20130 defeat to [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]] at [[Christie Park (stadium)|Christie Park]] on 13 December. He returned to Huddersfield on 29 December.\n\nOn 4 August 2009, Flynn joined local rivals Bradford City on a [[Bosman ruling|free transfer]]. He made his debut four days later in the 5\u20130 defeat by [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] at [[Meadow Lane]] and scored his first goal of the 2011\u201312 season in a 3\u20132 loss to Leeds United. On 28 April 2012 it was announced that he would leave Bradford as his contract was ended by mutual consent along with teammates [[Chris Mitchell (footballer born 1988)|Chris Mitchell]] and [[Craig Fagan]].\n\nOn 25 July 2012 he re-signed for home-town club Newport County. In the [[2012\u201313 Newport County A.F.C. season|2012\u201313 season]] he was part of the Newport team that finished 3rd in the league, reaching the Conference National playoffs. Newport County won the [[2013 Conference National play-off Final|playoff final]] versus Wrexham at [[Wembley Stadium]] 2\u20130 to return to the Football League after a 25-year absence with promotion to [[Football League Two]].<ref name=\"Wrexham 0-2 Newport\">{{Cite news\n| first = Dewi\n| last = Hughes\n| title = Wrexham 0\u20132 Newport\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22335600\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 5 May 2013\n| accessdate = 5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015 Flynn's playing contract came to an end and it was not extended by Newport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32703882|title=Newport County: Aaron O'Connor one of 11 senior players to leave|date=12 May 2015|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017 whilst first team coach at Newport Flynn registered as a player. He made his fourth debut for Newport in the League Two match on 28 January 2017 versus Hartlepool United as a second-half substitute.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38700944|title=Newport County 3\u20131 Hartlepool United|date=28 January 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching experience==\nHe earned his UEFA Pro Licence at the same time as [[Mikel Arteta]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nFlynn worked as academy manager for Newport County, before being released (as both player and coach) by Terry Butcher.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48176077|title=Michael Flynn: Newport manager's rise from would-be estate agent to club legend|date=6 May 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In 2015 he then joined [[Welsh Football League Division Two]] side [[Undy Athletic A.F.C.|Undy Athletic]] as player-coach, intend to combine this part-time role with a job as an estate agent or a publican.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk1\"/>\n\nIn August 2015, Newport County Supporters Trust took over interim control of the club, and appointed Flynn on a voluntary basis as club ambassador. He would later serve in other roles including marketing until October. On 8 October 2015 Flynn rejoined [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] as first team coach under new manager [[John Sheridan (footballer)|John Sheridan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34480662|title=Michael Flynn: Former player to continue on Newport County staff|date=9 October 2015|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In January 2016 [[Warren Feeney]] was appointed team manager and Flynn was retained as first team coach. In July 2016 Newport County appointed Flynn to a newly created role as Football and Business Development Director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/14601390.Former_midfielder_Flynn_excited_by_new_Exiles_role/|title=Former midfielder Flynn excited by new Exiles role|website=South Wales Argus}}</ref> In October 2016 Flynn again rejoined the Newport County coaching staff under newly appointed manager [[Graham Westley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37645958|title=Michael Flynn: Former midfielder returns to Newport County coaching team|date=13 October 2016|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/football/newportcounty/14800107.Michael_Flynn_returns_to_coaching_role_with_Newport_County/|title=Michael Flynn returns to coaching role with Newport County|website=South Wales Argus}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\n\nOn 9 March 2017 Flynn was appointed caretaker manager of Newport County for the remainder of the [[2016\u201317 Newport County A.F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]] following the sacking of Graham Westley with Newport 11 points adrift at the bottom of League Two.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39178177|title=Newport County sack manager Graham Westley|date=9 March 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Flynn said his wife didn't want him to take the job.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk1\"/> [[Wayne Hatswell]] returned to the club as Assistant Manager to Flynn. Flynn led the team to Football League survival, avoiding relegation with a win in the final match of the season and confirming the second 'great escape' in the club's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39753914|title=Newport County 2\u20131 Notts County|date=6 May 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 9 May 2017 Flynn was appointed permanent team manager on a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39854787|title=Mike Flynn appointed permanent Newport County manager|date=9 May 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 January 2018 a 2\u20131 home win over [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in the FA Cup third round meant Newport progressed to the FA Cup fourth round for the first time since 1979 and they were drawn at home to [[Premier League]] club Tottenham Hotspur.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42526173 |title=Newport County 2\u20131 Leeds United |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 January 2018 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref> On 27 January 2018 Newport achieved a 1\u20131 draw to force a replay at Tottenham's temporary home ground of [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42756217|title=Newport County 1\u20131 Tottenham Hotspur|first=Dafydd |last=Pritchard|date=27 January 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> Tottenham won the replay 2\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42882967|title=Tottenham Hotspur 2-0 Newport County|first=Michael |last=Pearlman|date=7 February 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> In Flynn's first full season in management Newport County finished the 2017\u201318 season in 11th place in League Two.\n\nThe following season, Flynn led Newport to another major [[2018-19 FA Cup|FA Cup]] upset, with a 2\u20131 victory over [[Premier League]] side Leicester City to send them through to the fourth round of the competition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pearlman |first1=Michael |title=Newport County 2\u20131 Leicester in FA Cup third round |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46713172 |accessdate=6 January 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 January 2019}}</ref> In the FA Cup fourth round Newport drew the away match 1\u20131 against Championship club Middlesbrough on 26 January 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46928649|title=Middlesbrough 1-1 Newport County in FA Cup third round|first=Michael |last=Pearlman|date=26 January 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> and on 5 February 2019 County won the replay at home 2\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47037237|title=Newport County 2-0 Middlesbrough in FA Cup fourth-round replay|date=5 February 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> The match provided a rare meeting for Flynn with fellow [[Pillgwenlly]]-born manager [[Tony Pulis]]. Pulis spoke highly about Newport's achievement after previous turmoil, describing Flynn as having achieved a \"fantastic job\" and also praising Newport Director of Football [[Lennie Lawrence]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/17379484.middlesbrough-boss-tony-pulis-full-of-respect-for-newport-county-and-manager-michael-flynn/|title=Tony Pulis won't do hometown club any favours on Saturday|website=South Wales Argus|language=en|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nCounty progressed to the FA Cup fifth round for the first time since 1949 and were drawn at home against reigning Premier League champions Manchester City. County lost the match 4\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47180807|title=Newport 1-4 Man City: Phil Foden double helps City into FA Cup quarter-finals|first=Michael |last=Pearlman|date=16 February 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> Before and after the match, Flynn received praise from a number of managers across the business, including his former UEFA pro-licence classmates Arteta and Henry, for progressing to the late stages of the competition. Flynn, a Liverpool fan, was also later invited by manager [[Jurgen Klopp]] to join a coaching session at [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]'s [[Melwood]] ground.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47138437|title=FA Cup: Goalkeeper's wife has twin girls and rise of the supermarket shelf-stacker|date=6 February 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|quote=\"We have had Mauricio Pochettino, Claude Puel, Thomas Christiansen, they are all fantastic managers but this is the creme de la creme. He is a master, somebody that I just idolise and probably the best in the business, along with Jurgen Klopp, because I am a Liverpool fan,\" Flynn said.}}</ref>\n\nNewport finished the [[2018\u201319 EFL League Two|2018\u201319 season]] in seventh place in League Two, thus qualifying for the [[2018 English Football League play-offs#League Two Final|League Two play-offs]]. In the semi-final against [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]], Newport drew the first leg 1\u20131 at home, drew the second leg 0\u20130 at Mansfield and then won the semi-final penalty shoot-out.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48165959|title=Mansfield Town 0-0 (3-5 pens) Newport County: Day sends County to Wembley|date=12 May 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> In the [[2019 EFL League Two play-off Final|League Two playoff final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] on 25 May 2019 Newport lost to [[Tranmere Rovers]], 1-0 after a goal in the 119th minute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48318580|title=League Two play-off final: Newport County 0-1 Tranmere Rovers|first=Michael |last=Pearlman|date=25 May 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 August 2019, Newport County faced [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] of the Premier League in Round 2 of the [[EFL Cup]], losing the tie 2\u20130.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49403011 Newport County v West Ham]</ref> In September 2019, Flynn was closely linked with the team manager vacancy at [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] following the departure of [[Danny Cowley]]. County went on to confirm they had granted permission to \"another EFL club\" to interview Flynn.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newport-county.co.uk/news/2019/september/statement-re-flynn-speculation/|title=CLUB STATEMENT {{!}} Manager Michael Flynn|website=www.newport-county.co.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> On 17 September Flynn confirmed through a club press release that he was no longer in talks for the prospective role.<ref name=\":0\" /> In October 2019 he signed a new contract with Newport, until June 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49926620|title=Michael Flynn: Manager handed new Newport County contract|date=3 October 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> Newport also reached the semi-final of the [[EFL Trophy]], losing to Salford City on penalties on 19 February 2020.<ref name=\"FA Trophy semi final\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51494329 FA Trophy semi final]</ref> On 19 February 2020 Newport reached the semi-final of the [[EFL Trophy]], losing to Salford City on penalties.<ref name=\"FA Trophy semi final\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nBorn in Newport, he was born to his mother Kerry and father John, both of Bettws. His mother had Michael at the age of 20 and he grew up with his great aunt Sheila and uncle Ted on Baldwin Street in the [[Pillgwenlly]] area of Newport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/12863919.first-person-newport-county-midfielder-and-youth-development-coach-michael-flynn/|title=FIRST PERSON: Newport County midfielder and youth development coach Michael Flynn|website=South Wales Argus|language=en|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref> His uncle worked at [[Newport Docks]]. Flynn has spoken of his uncle and aunt's Catholic values and its influence on his upbringing. He also described himself as a shy child, and a short but keen young footballer. He played for a range of youth sides including [[Albion Rovers F.C. (Newport)|Albion Rovers Under 10s]], Pill AFC, [[Newport Civil Service F.C.|Newport Civil Service]] and [[Newport YMCA A.F.C.|Newport YMCA]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/15476469.i-am-proud-to-be-from-newport-county-manager-michael-flynn/|title=FIRST PERSON: 'I am proud to be from Newport ' \u2013 County manager Michael Flynn|website=South Wales Argus|language=en|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nFlynn worked part-time jobs early in his career, stacking shelves while a youth player for Newport. He worked as a postman in 2001 prior to his first professional contract with Barry Town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theleaguepaper.com/featured/8193/newport-countys-great-escape-fills-flynn-with-pride/|title=Newport County's 'Great Escape' fills Flynn with pride|last=Ellis|first=Adam|date=18 May 2017|website=The League Paper|language=en-GB|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref> Flynn married his wife Victoria in 2016, and has five children; one daughter and two sons from previous relationships: Dionne (b. 2000), Charlie (b. 2014) and Theo (b. 2014) and two sons with his wife Victoria: Edward (b. 2015) and Samuel (b. 2017).<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/15483831.newport-county-manager-celebrates-birth-of-son-samuel-and-a-superb-1-0-win-at-coventry-city/|title=It's the perfect end to the perfect week for Exiles boss Michael Flynn|website=South Wales Argus|language=en|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nFlynn went to [[St Joseph's Roman Catholic High School, Newport|St Joseph's High School]] as a child, where he was a schoolmate of former [[West Ham United F.C.]] player and [[Wales national football team|Wales international]] [[James Collins (footballer, born 1983)|James Collins]], who is two years younger than Flynn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/football/newportcounty/17850117.newport-county-unlikely-sign-ex-wales-star-james-collins/|title=Newport County unlikely to sign ex-Wales star James Collins|last=Penman|first=Andrew|date=21 August 2019|website=South Wales Argus|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 September 2019}}</ref> Flynn attended [[Staffordshire University]] obtaining a 2:1 degree in BA Sports Journalism and Media Law. Flynn holds a [[UEFA Pro Licence]], which he obtained alongside [[Thierry Henry]] at the [[Football Association of Wales]] [[Dragon Park]] headquarters in 2013. He was previously a director of a Newport estate agency named Crook, Hudson & Flynn, and is now a director of estate agency David Spencer Ltd.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/06002485/officers|title=DAVID SPENCER LIMITED - Officers (free information from Companies House)|date= 24 March 2014|website=Companies House|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 10 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=3861 |title=Managers: Michael Flynn |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n|align=left|9 March 2017\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|178|71|47|60|decimals=1}}\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|178|71|47|60|decimals=1}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Newport County A.F.C. managers}}\n{{Newport County A.F.C. squad}}\n{{EFL League Two managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flynn, Michael}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Newport, Wales]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Newport County A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barry Town United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Wigan Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Darlington F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Undy A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:Cymru Premier players]]\n[[Category:Welsh football managers]]\n[[Category:Newport County A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Mike Flynn (footballer)||text=English football player [[Mike Flynn (footballer)|Michael Anthony Flynn]]. For other people with the same name see [[Michael Flynn (disambiguation)]]}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Michael Flynn\n| image = MichaelFlynn.jpg\n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|10|17|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|6550|Mike Flynn|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Wales<ref name=Hugman/>\n| height = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]<ref name=Hugman/>\n| currentclub = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] (manager)\n| clubnumber = \n| years1 = 1999\u20132000\n| years2 = 2000\u20132001\n| years3 = 2000\u20132001\n| years4 = 2001\u20132002\n| years5 = 2002\u20132005\n| years6 = 2004\n| years7 = 2005\u20132007\n| years8 = 2007\u20132008\n| years9 = 2008\u20132009\n| years10 = 2008\n| years11 = 2009\u20132012\n| years12 = 2012\u20132015\n| years13 = 2015\u20132017\n| years14 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs1 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| clubs2 = [[Barry Town F.C.|Barry Town]]\n| clubs3 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| clubs4 = [[Barry Town F.C.|Barry Town]]\n| clubs5 = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] (loan)\n| clubs7 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n| clubs8 = [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]\n| clubs9 = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n| clubs10 = \u2192 [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] (loan)\n| clubs11 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n| clubs12 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| clubs13 = [[Undy Athletic A.F.C.|Undy Athletic]]\n| clubs14 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| caps1 = 20\n| goals1 = 4\n| caps2 = 8\n| goals2 = 12\n| caps3 = 3\n| goals3 = 1\n| caps4 = 12\n| goals4 = 12\n| caps5 = 37\n| goals5 = 2\n| caps6 = 6\n| goals6 = 0\n| caps7 = 97\n| goals7 = 19\n| caps8 = 26\n| goals8 = 3\n| caps9 = 25\n| goals9 = 4\n| caps10 = 4\n| goals10 = 0\n| caps11 = 91\n| goals11 = 10\n| caps12 = 82\n| goals12 = 5\n| caps13 = 4\n| goals13 = 3\n| caps14 = 5\n| goals14 = 0\n| totalcaps = 420\n| totalgoals = 75\n| manageryears1 = 2015\n| managerclubs1 = [[Undy Athletic A.F.C.|Undy Athletic]]\n| manageryears2 = 2017\n| managerclubs2 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] (caretaker)\n| manageryears3 = 2017\u2013\n| managerclubs3 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n}}\n'''Michael Flynn''' (born 17 October 1980) is a Welsh professional [[Manager (association football)|football manager]] and former [[Football player|player]] who played as a [[midfielder]]. He is the manager of {{English football updater|NewportC}} club [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]].\n\nFlynn began his career with Newport County, becoming a professional with [[Barry Town F.C.|Barry Town]] before his break out with [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]. He appeared 91 times for [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]. He returned to Newport County and played while obtaining his UEFA Pro License, however he became caretaker manager in 2017 amid a relegation battle.\n\nAfter 2017's 'Great Escape', Newport County won FA Cup fixtures against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]. In 2018 Newport also played [[The Premier League|Premier League]] team [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and in 2019 [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. In 2018\u201319 Flynn led Newport to the [[2019 EFL League Two play-off Final]] against [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Flynn started his career playing for [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] in 1999. A move to [[League of Wales]] club Barry Town beckoned in 2000. After forty goals in two seasons, including a goal in a 3\u20131 win over [[F.C. Porto]] in the second qualifying round of the Champions League, he moved to [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in the [[2002-03 in English football|2002\u201303 season]].\n\nFlynn spent a lot of his time on the substitutes' bench as Wigan won [[Football League Division Two|Division Two]] title. He made seventeen appearances in the league, fourteen of which came from the bench, and scored one goal. The next season did not start any better for Flynn as he started just one game and made seven appearances from the bench before he was loaned to then League One side [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]], where he started six times in the league and once in the [[FA Cup]] before returning to Wigan.\n\nIn the January [[transfer window]] of [[2004-05 in English football|that season]], Flynn joined [[Football League Championship|Championship]] strugglers Gillingham on a [[free transfer (football)|free transfer]]. Despite his instant success, and his three goals in sixteen starts, Gillingham were relegated to League One on the last day of the season.\n\nAlthough injury affected his [[2005-06 in English football|2005\u201306 season]], Flynn scored six goals. He took over as captain for the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307 season]] and became top scorer with twelve goals.\n\nIt was announced on 8 May 2007 that Flynn had been offered a new contract with Gillingham. He chose not to sign, and left the club when his contract expired at the end of June 2007.\n\nOn 5 July 2007, Flynn signed a one-year contract with [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]], with an option for a further year. On 3 December 2007, Flynn scored his first goal for Blackpool in the club's 1\u20131 away draw against [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]. On 7 May 2008 he was released by Blackpool.\nOn 23 July 2008, he became [[Stan Ternent]]'s fifth signing at League One side [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]. He, along with five other players, made his Town debut in the 1\u20131 draw against [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] at the [[Galpharm Stadium]] on 9 August 2008. On 27 August he scored his first goal for Huddersfield in the second round of the [[Football League Cup 2008-09|League Cup]] against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]. Town went on to lose the game 2\u20131. His first league goals for Town came in the 3\u20132 win over [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] at the [[Galpharm Stadium]] on 20 September 2008.\n\nFollowing a short spell on the sidelines following a [[hamstring]] injury, he joined [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] on loan on 27 November 2008. He made his debut in the 1\u20130 defeat to [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]] at [[Christie Park (stadium)|Christie Park]] on 13 December. He returned to Huddersfield on 29 December.\n\nOn 4 August 2009, Flynn joined local rivals Bradford City on a [[Bosman ruling|free transfer]]. He made his debut four days later in the 5\u20130 defeat by [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] at [[Meadow Lane]] and scored his first goal of the 2011\u201312 season in a 3\u20132 loss to Leeds United. On 28 April 2012 it was announced that he would leave Bradford as his contract was ended by mutual consent along with teammates [[Chris Mitchell (footballer born 1988)|Chris Mitchell]] and [[Craig Fagan]].\n\nOn 25 July 2012 he re-signed for home-town club Newport County. In the [[2012\u201313 Newport County A.F.C. season|2012\u201313 season]] he was part of the Newport team that finished 3rd in the league, reaching the Conference National playoffs. Newport County won the [[2013 Conference National play-off Final|playoff final]] versus Wrexham at [[Wembley Stadium]] 2\u20130 to return to the Football League after a 25-year absence with promotion to [[Football League Two]].<ref name=\"Wrexham 0-2 Newport\">{{Cite news\n| first = Dewi\n| last = Hughes\n| title = Wrexham 0\u20132 Newport\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22335600\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 5 May 2013\n| accessdate = 5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015 Flynn's playing contract came to an end and it was not extended by Newport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32703882|title=Newport County: Aaron O'Connor one of 11 senior players to leave|date=12 May 2015|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017 whilst first team coach at Newport Flynn registered as a player. He made his fourth debut for Newport in the League Two match on 28 January 2017 versus Hartlepool United as a second-half substitute.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38700944|title=Newport County 3\u20131 Hartlepool United|date=28 January 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching experience==\nHe earned his UEFA Pro Licence at the same time as [[Mikel Arteta]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nFlynn worked as academy manager for Newport County, before being released (as both player and coach) by Terry Butcher.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48176077|title=Michael Flynn: Newport manager's rise from would-be estate agent to club legend|date=6 May 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In 2015 he then joined [[Welsh Football League Division Two]] side [[Undy Athletic A.F.C.|Undy Athletic]] as player-coach, intend to combine this part-time role with a job as an estate agent or a publican.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk1\"/>\n\nIn August 2015, Newport County Supporters Trust took over interim control of the club, and appointed Flynn on a voluntary basis as club ambassador. He would later serve in other roles including marketing until October. On 8 October 2015 Flynn rejoined [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] as first team coach under new manager [[John Sheridan (footballer)|John Sheridan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34480662|title=Michael Flynn: Former player to continue on Newport County staff|date=9 October 2015|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In January 2016 [[Warren Feeney]] was appointed team manager and Flynn was retained as first team coach. In July 2016 Newport County appointed Flynn to a newly created role as Football and Business Development Director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/14601390.Former_midfielder_Flynn_excited_by_new_Exiles_role/|title=Former midfielder Flynn excited by new Exiles role|website=South Wales Argus}}</ref> In October 2016 Flynn again rejoined the Newport County coaching staff under newly appointed manager [[Graham Westley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37645958|title=Michael Flynn: Former midfielder returns to Newport County coaching team|date=13 October 2016|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/football/newportcounty/14800107.Michael_Flynn_returns_to_coaching_role_with_Newport_County/|title=Michael Flynn returns to coaching role with Newport County|website=South Wales Argus}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\n\nOn 9 March 2017 Flynn was appointed caretaker manager of Newport County for the remainder of the [[2016\u201317 Newport County A.F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]] following the sacking of Graham Westley with Newport 11 points adrift at the bottom of League Two.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39178177|title=Newport County sack manager Graham Westley|date=9 March 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Flynn said his wife didn't want him to take the job.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk1\"/> [[Wayne Hatswell]] returned to the club as Assistant Manager to Flynn. Flynn led the team to Football League survival, avoiding relegation with a win in the final match of the season and confirming the second 'great escape' in the club's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39753914|title=Newport County 2\u20131 Notts County|date=6 May 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 9 May 2017 Flynn was appointed permanent team manager on a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39854787|title=Mike Flynn appointed permanent Newport County manager|date=9 May 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 January 2018 a 2\u20131 home win over [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in the FA Cup third round meant Newport progressed to the FA Cup fourth round for the first time since 1979 and they were drawn at home to [[Premier League]] club Tottenham Hotspur.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42526173 |title=Newport County 2\u20131 Leeds United |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 January 2018 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref> On 27 January 2018 Newport achieved a 1\u20131 draw to force a replay at Tottenham's temporary home ground of [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42756217|title=Newport County 1\u20131 Tottenham Hotspur|first=Dafydd |last=Pritchard|date=27 January 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> Tottenham won the replay 2\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42882967|title=Tottenham Hotspur 2-0 Newport County|first=Michael |last=Pearlman|date=7 February 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> In Flynn's first full season in management Newport County finished the 2017\u201318 season in 11th place in League Two.\n\nThe following season, Flynn led Newport to another major [[2018-19 FA Cup|FA Cup]] upset, with a 2\u20131 victory over [[Premier League]] side Leicester City to send them through to the fourth round of the competition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pearlman |first1=Michael |title=Newport County 2\u20131 Leicester in FA Cup third round |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46713172 |accessdate=6 January 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 January 2019}}</ref> In the FA Cup fourth round Newport drew the away match 1\u20131 against Championship club Middlesbrough on 26 January 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46928649|title=Middlesbrough 1-1 Newport County in FA Cup third round|first=Michael |last=Pearlman|date=26 January 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> and on 5 February 2019 County won the replay at home 2\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47037237|title=Newport County 2-0 Middlesbrough in FA Cup fourth-round replay|date=5 February 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> The match provided a rare meeting for Flynn with fellow [[Pillgwenlly]]-born manager [[Tony Pulis]]. Pulis spoke highly about Newport's achievement after previous turmoil, describing Flynn as having achieved a \"fantastic job\" and also praising Newport Director of Football [[Lennie Lawrence]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/17379484.middlesbrough-boss-tony-pulis-full-of-respect-for-newport-county-and-manager-michael-flynn/|title=Tony Pulis won't do hometown club any favours on Saturday|website=South Wales Argus|language=en|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nCounty progressed to the FA Cup fifth round for the first time since 1949 and were drawn at home against reigning Premier League champions Manchester City. County lost the match 4\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47180807|title=Newport 1-4 Man City: Phil Foden double helps City into FA Cup quarter-finals|first=Michael |last=Pearlman|date=16 February 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> Before and after the match, Flynn received praise from a number of managers across the business, including his former UEFA pro-licence classmates Arteta and Henry, for progressing to the late stages of the competition. Flynn, a Liverpool fan, was also later invited by manager [[Jurgen Klopp]] to join a coaching session at [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]'s [[Melwood]] ground.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47138437|title=FA Cup: Goalkeeper's wife has twin girls and rise of the supermarket shelf-stacker|date=6 February 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|quote=\"We have had Mauricio Pochettino, Claude Puel, Thomas Christiansen, they are all fantastic managers but this is the creme de la creme. He is a master, somebody that I just idolise and probably the best in the business, along with Jurgen Klopp, because I am a Liverpool fan,\" Flynn said.}}</ref>\n\nNewport finished the [[2018\u201319 EFL League Two|2018\u201319 season]] in seventh place in League Two, thus qualifying for the [[2018 English Football League play-offs#League Two Final|League Two play-offs]]. In the semi-final against [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]], Newport drew the first leg 1-1 at home, drew the second leg 0-0 at Mansfield and then won the semi-final penalty shoot-out.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48165959|title=Mansfield Town 0-0 (3-5 pens) Newport County: Day sends County to Wembley|date=12 May 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> In the [[2019 EFL League Two play-off Final|League Two playoff final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] on 25 May 2019 Newport lost to [[Tranmere Rovers]], 1-0 after a goal in the 119th minute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48318580|title=League Two play-off final: Newport County 0-1 Tranmere Rovers|first=Michael |last=Pearlman|date=25 May 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 August 2019, Newport County faced [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] of the Premier League in Round 2 of the [[EFL Cup]], losing the tie 2-0.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49403011 Newport County v West Ham]</ref> In September 2019, Flynn was closely linked with the team manager vacancy at [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] following the departure of [[Danny Cowley]]. County went on to confirm they had granted permission to \"another EFL club\" to interview Flynn.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newport-county.co.uk/news/2019/september/statement-re-flynn-speculation/|title=CLUB STATEMENT {{!}} Manager Michael Flynn|website=www.newport-county.co.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> On 17 September Flynn confirmed through a club press release that he was no longer in talks for the prospective role.<ref name=\":0\" /> In October 2019 he signed a new contract with Newport, until June 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49926620|title=Michael Flynn: Manager handed new Newport County contract|date=3 October 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> Newport also reached the semi-final of the [[EFL Trophy]], losing to Salford City on penalties on 19 February 2020.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51494329 FA Trophy semi final]</ref> On 19 February 2020 Newport reached the semi-final of the [[EFL Trophy]], losing to Salford City on penalties.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51494329 FA Trophy semi final]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nBorn in Newport, he was born to his mother Kerry and father John, both of Bettws. His mother had Michael at the age of 20 and he grew up with his great aunt Sheila and uncle Ted on Baldwin Street in the [[Pillgwenlly]] area of Newport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/12863919.first-person-newport-county-midfielder-and-youth-development-coach-michael-flynn/|title=FIRST PERSON: Newport County midfielder and youth development coach Michael Flynn|website=South Wales Argus|language=en|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref> His uncle worked at [[Newport Docks]]. Flynn has spoken of his uncle and aunt's Catholic values and its influence on his upbringing. He also described himself as a shy child, and a short but keen young footballer. He played for a range of youth sides including [[Albion Rovers F.C. (Newport)|Albion Rovers Under 10s]], Pill AFC, [[Newport Civil Service F.C.|Newport Civil Service]] and [[Newport YMCA A.F.C.|Newport YMCA]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/15476469.i-am-proud-to-be-from-newport-county-manager-michael-flynn/|title=FIRST PERSON: 'I am proud to be from Newport ' \u2013 County manager Michael Flynn|website=South Wales Argus|language=en|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nFlynn worked part-time jobs early in his career, stacking shelves while a youth player for Newport. He worked as a postman in 2001 prior to his first professional contract with Barry Town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theleaguepaper.com/featured/8193/newport-countys-great-escape-fills-flynn-with-pride/|title=Newport County's 'Great Escape' fills Flynn with pride|last=Ellis|first=Adam|date=18 May 2017|website=The League Paper|language=en-GB|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref> Flynn married his wife Victoria in 2016, and has five children; one daughter and two sons from previous relationships: Dionne (b. 2000), Charlie (b. 2014) and Theo (b. 2014) and two sons with his wife Victoria: Edward (b. 2015) and Samuel (b. 2017).<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/15483831.newport-county-manager-celebrates-birth-of-son-samuel-and-a-superb-1-0-win-at-coventry-city/|title=It's the perfect end to the perfect week for Exiles boss Michael Flynn|website=South Wales Argus|language=en|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nFlynn went to [[St Joseph's Roman Catholic High School, Newport|St Joseph's High School]] as a child, where he was a schoolmate of former [[West Ham United F.C.]] player and [[Wales national football team|Wales international]] [[James Collins (footballer, born 1983)|James Collins]], who is two years younger than Flynn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/football/newportcounty/17850117.newport-county-unlikely-sign-ex-wales-star-james-collins/|title=Newport County unlikely to sign ex-Wales star James Collins|last=Penman|first=Andrew|date=21 August 2019|website=South Wales Argus|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 September 2019}}</ref> Flynn attended [[Staffordshire University]] obtaining a 2:1 degree in BA Sports Journalism and Media Law. Flynn holds a [[UEFA Pro Licence]], which he obtained alongside [[Thierry Henry]] at the [[Football Association of Wales]] [[Dragon Park]] headquarters in 2013. He was previously a director of a Newport estate agency named Crook, Hudson & Flynn, and is now a director of estate agency David Spencer Ltd.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/06002485/officers|title=DAVID SPENCER LIMITED - Officers (free information from Companies House)|date= 24 March 2014|website=Companies House|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 10 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=3861 |title=Managers: Michael Flynn |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n|align=left|9 March 2017\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|178|71|47|60|decimals=1}}\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|178|71|47|60|decimals=1}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links=