}\n\n|combined total= 247.59 ('''WR''')\n|combined date= [[2019\u201320 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2019\u201320 Grand Prix Final]]\n|SP score= 85.45 ('''WR''')\n|SP date= [[2019\u201320 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2019\u201320 Grand Prix Final]]\n|FS score= 162.14\n|FS date= [[2019\u201320 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2019\u201320 Grand Prix Final]]\n|show-medals= yes\n| medaltemplates= <!-- see [[Template:MedalRelatedTemplates]] -->\n{{MedalCountry | {{RUS}}}}\n{{MedalSport | [[Figure skating]]: [[Single skating|Ladies' singles]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2020 European Figure Skating Championships|2020 Graz]]|Ladies' singles}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[ISU Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|Grand Prix Final]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019\u201320 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2019\u201320 Torino]]|Ladies' singles}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Junior Figure Skating Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2018 World Junior Figure Skating Championships|2018 Sofia]]|Ladies' singles}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[ISU Junior Grand Prix Final|Junior Grand Prix Final]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018\u201319 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2018\u201319 Vancouver]]|Ladies' singles}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2017\u201318 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2017\u201318 Nagoya]]|Ladies' singles}}\n}}\n\n'''Alena Sergeyevna Kostornaia''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u0451\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0430\u044f}}, born 24 August 2003) is a Russian [[figure skater]]. She is the [[2020 European Figure Skating Championships|2020 European]] champion, the [[2019\u201320 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2019\u201320 Grand Prix Final]] champion, the [[2019 Internationaux de France]] champion, the [[2019 NHK Trophy]] champion and the [[2019 CS Finlandia Trophy]] champion. Competing domestically, she is the [[2020 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2020 Russian national]] silver medalist, and a two-time [[Russian Figure Skating Championships|Russian national]] bronze medalist (2018, 2019).\n\nOn the junior level, she is the [[2018 World Junior Figure Skating Championships|2018 Junior World]] silver medalist, the [[2018\u201319 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2018\u201319 Junior Grand Prix Final]] champion, the [[2017\u201318 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2017\u201318 Junior Grand Prix Final]] silver medalist, and a two-time [[Russian Figure Skating Championships|Russian junior national]] silver medalist (2018, 2019).\n\nKostornaia is the tenth woman in history to have landed the [[Axel jump|triple Axel jump]] in a senior international competition. She is the third woman after teammate [[Elizaveta Tuktamysheva]] and [[Rika Kihira]] of Japan to attempt and land the maximum number of triple jumps allowed in one senior international competition: four in the short program and eight in the long program (see [[Zayak rule]]). She first accomplished this at the [[2019 Internationaux de France]], and later landed all twelve triples cleanly at the [[2019\u201320 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2019\u201320 Grand Prix Final]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isuresults.com/results/season1920/gpjpn2019/|title=ISU GP NHK Trophy 2019|website=www.isuresults.com|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isuresults.com/results/season1920/gpf1920/|title=ISU Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final 2019|website=www.isuresults.com|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\nShe currently holds the world records for the highest [[List of highest scores in figure skating#Ladies|total]] and [[List of highest scores in figure skating#Ladies|short program]] scores, as well as the [[List of highest junior scores in figure skating#Ladies|junior]] world record for the highest short program score, in ladies' skating.\n\nKostornaia is currently the sixth highest ranked [[singles skating|ladies' singles]] skater in world by the [[International Skating Union]] following the [[2019-20 figure skating season]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nKostornaia was born on 24 August 2003 in [[Moscow]] to parents Sergei and Tatiana. She has a younger brother, Stepan.<ref name=\"ISU-1718\" /> Although she registers her name as \"Alena\" with the ISU, Kostornaia uses the romanization of \"Aliona\" on her official [[Instagram]] account.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Career ==\n=== Early career ===\nKostornaia began learning to skate in 2007.<ref name=\"ISU-1718\" /> From 2012 to 2017, she was coached by Elena Zhgun in Moscow.<ref name=fskate />\n\nKostornaia had an injury in 2016.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} She finished 16th at the [[2017 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2017 Russian Junior Championships]]. [[Eteri Tutberidze]] and [[Sergei Dudakov]] became her coaches in 2017.<ref name=fskate />\n\n=== 2017\u20132018 season: Junior international debut ===\nKostornaia's international debut came in early October 2017 at a [[2017\u201318 ISU Junior Grand Prix]] (JGP) competition in [[Gdansk]], [[Poland]]; ranked first in the short program and second in the free skate, she won the gold medal by a margin of 1.36 points over the silver medalist, her teammate and training partner [[Daria Panenkova]].<ref name=JGPPOL2017 /> She won silver behind [[Sofia Samodurova]] at [[ISU Junior Grand Prix in Italy|JGP Italy]] by a margin of 0.04 points.<ref name=JGPITA2017 /> Her placements qualified her for the [[2017\u201318 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2017\u201318 Junior Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final]], where she won silver, placing second in the short program, and first in the free skate. On the senior level, Kostornaia won bronze at the [[2018 Russian Figure Skating Championships]]. She later won silver at the [[Russian Junior Figure Skating Championships|2018 Russian Junior Championships]] behind teammate [[Alexandra Trusova]] by a margin of 0.58 points.\n\nIn March 2018, Kostornaia competed at the [[2018 World Junior Figure Skating Championships|2018 World Junior Championships]]. She placed second in the short program and the free skate, winning the silver medal behind Trusova.\n\n=== 2018\u20132019 season ===\n[[File:2019 Russian Figure Skating Championships Alena Kostornaia 2018-12-21 15-29-18 1545444611.jpg|thumb|right|Kostornaia (center) with her coaches at the [[2019 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2019 Russian Championships]].]]\nKostornaia had learned to perform a [[Axel jump|triple Axel]] in the preceding year, and had originally planned to introduce it into competition. However, she lost the jump following growth during the offseason.<ref name=GS181208 /> Kostornaia started her season by competing in the [[2018\u201319 ISU Junior Grand Prix|2018 JGP series]]. At her first JGP event of the season, she won the gold medal in [[Linz]], [[Austria]]. She was ranked first in both the short program and the free skate and won the gold medal by a margin of more than 11 points over the silver medalist, her teammate [[Alena Kanysheva]].<ref name=JGPAUT2018 />\n\nShe skated her second JGP event of the season at [[ISU Junior Grand Prix in the Czech Republic|JGP Ostrava]], where she was again ranked first in both the short program and the free skate. She won the gold medal by a margin of about 2 points over the silver medalist, [[Kim Ye-lim (figure skater)|Kim Ye-lim]].<ref name=JGPCZE2018 /> With two JGP victories, she qualified for the [[2018\u20132019 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2018\u201319 Junior Grand Prix Final]], where she won the gold medal after placing first in both the short program and the free skate. She outscored her teammate and training partner Trusova by about 2.5 points. At this event, Kostornaia scored her personal best score of 217.98 points and she also set a new junior-level ladies' record for the [[List of highest junior scores in figure skating#Short program score 2|short program]] (76.32 points).<ref name=GS181207 /><ref name=GS181208 />\n\nAt the [[2019 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2019 Russian Championships]], Kostornaia placed third in the short program due to a fall during her step sequence, which she attributed to being \"too relaxed\" as she was nearing the end of the program and had already completed all of her jumping passes.<ref name=GS181221 /> She then placed third in the free skate as well, winning her second consecutive national bronze medal.<ref name=GS181222 />\n\nKostornaia participated in the 2019 Russian Junior Championships, where she won the short program and placed second in the free skate. She was ranked second overall, winning her second consecutive junior national silver medal. After the event, she was named to the Russian team for the [[2019 World Junior Figure Skating Championships|2019 World Junior Championships]] along with training mates Trusova and [[Anna Shcherbakova]]. However, on March 4, the first day of the event, Kostornaia withdrew from the competition due to a medical condition, subsequently revealed by choreographer [[Daniil Gleikhengauz]] to be a leg inflammation that would require four weeks away from training. She was replaced by [[Ksenia Sinitsyna]].<ref name=RS190310 />\n\n=== 2019\u20132020 season: Senior international debut and European title ===\nFor her programs, Kostornaia retained her short program from the previous season, and revised a ''[[Twilight (film series)|Twilight]]''-themed exhibition program from the previous year to serve as her free skate, citing how much she enjoyed skating it.<ref name=GS191102 /> Shortly after debuting her programs at the Russian test skates, Kostornaia resumed training the [[Axel jump|triple Axel jump]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fs-gossips.com/alena-kostornaia-of-course-its-very-disappointing-when-everyone-does-it-but-you-dont/|title=Alena Kostornaia: Of course, it's very disappointing when everyone does it, but you don't|last=|first=|date=|website=FS Gossips|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Kostornaia began her season at the [[2019 CS Finlandia Trophy]], marking her senior international debut, where she placed first in both the short program and free skate segments of the event. She incorporated two triple Axels in her free skate, becoming the tenth woman in history to land the jump in an international competition, and earned a total combined score of 234.84, 22.31 points ahead of silver medalist [[Elizaveta Tuktamysheva]].<ref name=OC191014 />\n\n[[File:2019 Internationaux de France Saturday medals ladies 8D9A2656.jpg|thumb|right|Kostornaia (center) with [[Alina Zagitova]] (left) and [[Mariah Bell]] (right) at the [[2019 Internationaux de France]] medal ceremony.]]\nMaking her [[2019-20 ISU Grand Prix of Figure Skating|senior Grand Prix]] debut at the [[2019 Internationaux de France]], Kostornaia ranked first in the short program, incorporating a triple Axel into it for the first time.<ref name=GS191101 /> She then became the fourth woman ever, after [[Mao Asada]], [[Rika Kihira]] and Elizaveta Tuktamysheva, to land two fully rotated triple Axels in a free skate, placing first in the segment with a personal best score of 159.45 points. She took the gold medal over training mate and reigning [[2019 World Figure Skating Championships|World]] and [[2018 Winter Olympics|Olympic]] champion [[Alina Zagitova]] by a margin of 19.94 points.<ref name=GS191102 /> At the [[2019 NHK Trophy]], Kostornaia performed a clean short program with a successful triple Axel to place first in that segment, 5.15 points over [[Rika Kihira]], who also landed a triple Axel, and set a new [[List of highest scores in figure skating#Ladies|world record]] score of 85.04 for the ladies' short program at the senior level.<ref name=GS191122 /> In the free, she again placed first and became the champion with a personal best total score of 240.00. Kostornaia thus became the top qualifier for the [[2019\u201320 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|Grand Prix Final]] in [[Turin|Torino]], with two gold medal finishes and 30 points overall.<ref name=GS191123 />\n\nAt the [[2019\u201320 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2019\u201320 Grand Prix Final]], she topped her own world record by scoring 85.45 in the short program, placing first.<ref name=GS191206 /> In spite of having the only clean free skate amongst the ladies, Kostornaia ranked second in that segment, 0.51 point behind teammate Anna Shcherbakova. However, her lead from the short program was enough not only to win her the title by almost 7 points over Shcherbakova, but also to help her break the [[List of highest scores in figure skating#Best total scores 2|world record for the combined total score in ladies' singles skating]], previously held by Alexandra Trusova. She became the fifth figure skater in any discipline to win the [[ISU Junior Grand Prix Final|Junior Grand Prix Final]] and [[Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|Grand Prix Final]] in consecutive years.<ref name=GS191208 />\n\nKostornaia competed next at the [[2020 Russian Figure Skating Championships|2020 Russian National championships]], where she again won the short program, setting a ten-point lead over second-place Anna Shcherbakova.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goh |first1=ZK |title=Alena Kostornaia blows opponents away to lead Russian nationals after short program |url=https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/stories/news/detail/alena-kostornaia-russian-national-figure-skating-short-program/ |website=Olympic Channel}}</ref> However, she made mistakes in the free skate, with imperfect landings on her double Axel and triple flip-triple toe loop combination, and placed second in that segment to become the national silver medalist, two points behind Shcherbakova. This result secured her a spot in the European and World teams.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goh |first1=ZK |title=Anna Shcherbakova retains Russian national title as Medvedeva withdraws and ends season |url=https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/stories/news/detail/anna-shcherbakova-free-skate-russian-title-medvedeva-withdraws/ |website=Olympic Channel}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2020 European Figure Skating Championships|2020 European Championships]], Kostornaia was in the lead following a clean short program.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jiwani |first1=Rory |title=Alena Kostornaia leads after European Championships short program |url=https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/stories/news/detail/figure-skating-alena-kostornaia-leads-european-short-graz/ |website=Olympic Channel}}</ref> She placed second in the free skate behind Shcherbakova, receiving a deduction for falling on her last jumping pass, a [[Lutz jump|triple lutz]], but still scored enough to claim the European title by three points. Upon being interviewed after her victory, she expressed surprise at the results, as she had not expected to win in light of her mistake.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Browne |first1=Ken |title=Alena Kostornaia wins European Figure Skating Championships in Russian '3A' clean sweep |url=https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/stories/news/detail/scherbakova-alexandra-trusova-european-championships-2020/ |website=Olympic Channel}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2020 World Figure Skating Championships|2020 World Championships]] were cancelled over concern about the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Kostornaia officially ended her season, having gone undefeated at every international competition of her senior debut.\n\n== Public life ==\nIn February 2020, Kostornaia was awarded the Silver Doe Prize and named the best athlete of 2019 by the Federation of Sports Journalists of Russia.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Programs ==\n[[File:2017-2018 ISU Junior Grand Prix Final Alena Kostornaia jsfb dave9338.jpg|thumb|right|Kostornaia performing a [[Biellmann spin]] at the [[2017-2018 Grand Prix of Figure Skating Final|2017-2018 Junior Grand Prix Final]].]]\n{|class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n! Season\n! [[Short program (figure skating)|Short program]]\n! [[Free skating]]\n! Exhibition\n|-\n! 2019\u20132020<br /> <ref name=ISU-1920 />\n|\n* The Departure (Lullaby)<br />{{small| (from ''[[The Leftovers (TV series)|The Leftovers]]'')<br /> by [[Max Richter]]}}\n* November<br />{{small| by [[Max Richter]]<br /> choreo. by [[Daniil Gleikhengauz]]}}\n|\n''[[Twilight (novel series)|Twilight]]''\n* New Moon (The Meadow)<br /> {{small| (from ''[[The Twilight Saga: New Moon]]'')<br /> by [[Alexandre Desplat]]}}\n* [[Eyes on Fire]]<br /> {{small| by [[Blue Foundation]]}}\n* [[Supermassive Black Hole (song)|Supermassive Black Hole]]<br /> {{small| by [[Muse (band)|Muse]]<br /> choreo. by [[Daniil Gleikhengauz]]}}\n|\n* [[Never Tear Us Apart]]<br /> {{small| (from [[Fifty Shades Freed (film)|Fifty Shades Freed]])<br /> performed by [[Bishop Briggs]]}}\n----\n* Eyes on Fire<br /> {{small| by [[Blue Foundation]]}}\n* [[Supermassive Black Hole (song)|Supermassive Black Hole]]<br /> {{small| by [[Muse (band)|Muse]]}}\n|-\n! 2018\u20132019<br /> <ref name=ISU-1819 />\n|\n* The Departure (Lullaby)<br />{{small| (from ''[[The Leftovers (TV series)|The Leftovers]]'')<br /> by [[Max Richter]]}}\n* November<br />{{small| by [[Max Richter]]<br /> choreo. by [[Daniil Gleikhengauz]]}}\n|\nRomeo and Juliet\n* [[Kissing You (Des'ree song)|Kissing You]]<br />{{small| by [[Des'ree]], [[Timothy Atack]]<br /> arranged by [[Craig Armstrong (composer)|Craig Armstrong]]}}\n* Forbidden Love<br />{{small| (from ''[[Romeo & Juliet (2013 film)|Romeo and Juliet]]'')<br /> by [[Abel Korzeniowski]]}}\n* [[Love Theme from Romeo and Juliet]]<br />{{small| by [[Nino Rota]]<br /> arranged by [[Henry Mancini]]<br /> choreo. by [[Daniil Gleikhengauz]]}}\n|\n* Dos cadencias sobre \"Adi\u00f3s Nonino\"<br /> {{small| originally by [[Astor Piazzolla]]<br /> by [[Pablo Ziegler]]<br /> choreo. by [[Eteri Tutberidze]]}}\n----\n* Eyes on Fire<br /> {{small| by [[Blue Foundation]]}}\n* [[Supermassive Black Hole (song)|Supermassive Black Hole]]<br